<HEAD>Brazil Boat Disaster Sparks Outcry Against Impunity Of Rich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report. ^By LISA GENASCI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sinking New Year's Eve of an overcrowded tourist boat off <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION> has sparked a nationwide outcry against what many Brazilians feel is the impunity of the rich and powerful and a general disrespect for law. In public demonstrations, Brazilians have made the tragedy, in which 52 passengers and crew died, a forum to rail against a widespread sense that in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> people in the right places can get away with lawbreaking _ from running red lights to hiring professional killers. `` Some of the worst vices of the Brazilian soul came to light the moment the boat sank: facility to bribe, irresponsibility and the failure to assist fellow citizens in trouble,'' the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Jornal </ORGANIZATION> do Brasil of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION> said in an editorial. There has been no accurate count of the number of revelers on the Bateau Mouche when it capsized and sank on its way to an annual fireworks display off <LOCATION> Copacabana </LOCATION> beach. A widely accepted figure is 150. The flat-bottomed river boat was built to carry 20 passengers. Survivors claim it was dangerously overcrowded and listing badly in rough water and that lifejackets were not readily accessible. There are accusations _ as yet unproved _ that <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> guards who inspected the Bateau Mouche just two hours before it went down were paid off to allow it to venture into the open sea. The navy and the police are bickering over which group should investigate the sinking. There is widespread fear that no one will be held responsible _ as happened so often before here in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest country, in highway and maritime tragedies, fires and collapses of buildings and freeways. In 1981, for example, two riverboat sinkings in <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> waters claimed about 500 lives. Both resulted from overcrowding, yet no one was ever prosecuted. `` The sinking of the Bateau Mouche is a portrait of our reality,'' political commentator <PERSON> Alexandre </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said in a syndicated newspaper column. `` We were already irresponsible, now we are becoming inhuman.'' `` There is a cultural tradition of disregarding security norms, of negligence,'' said <PERSON> Evaristo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Moraes </PERSON>, a lawyer for the owners of the Bateau Mouche. `` We need to look at our mentality, which believes that laws are always flexible.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Moraes </PERSON> added, however, that in the case of the boat disaster, `` I am convinced my clients had no responsibility whatsoever.'' Indeed, one of the owners of the boat initially told reporters that `` panic among the passengers'' was the cause of the tragedy. <PERSON> Paulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>, a son-in-law of the Bateau Mouche's 50-year-old captain, <PERSON> Camilo </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON>, who drowned, told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>, `` <PERSON> Camilo </PERSON> did n't want to go out He called us to say the boat was overloaded and the sea was too rough. But he had no choice. He would lose his job if he did n't sail.'' Brazilians are proud of what they call `` jeitinho,'' or a `` little way'' of cutting through red tape, avoiding a traffic ticket or eliminating a problem that has become intertwined with self-definitions of national character. There is a whole professional category known as `` despachantes,'' whose job consists basically of paying off the right people. A recent prime-time TV soap opera, `` Vale Tudo -LRB- Anything Goes -RRB-, drew ratings of 80 percent with its portrayals of greed, conniving, corruption and deceit among it principal characters. But it is n't exclusively a lack of respect for laws that has generated a sense of impunity in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, said Deputy Justice Minister <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichenberg </PERSON>. `` This also has grown from a tremendous lack of human and material resources,'' he said. `` We often are physically and financially unable to enforce the law.'' Many Brazilians are determined that the Bateau Mouche case not be forgotten. Theater and movie personalities _ outraged by the drowning of the well-known actress <PERSON> Yara </PERSON> <PERSON> Amaral </PERSON> _ along with <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> city </LOCATION> councilmen and other well known figures have organized to demand that police determine responsibility in the sinking. Brazilians also have rallied around the shooting death in December of the internationally known ecologist <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendes </PERSON>, who sought to defend the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION>'s ecology and its poor peasants against the interests of powerful landowners. Many employ private gunmen to eliminate enemies. According to <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based human rights organization, about 1,000 peasants, ecologists and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priests, who defend landless farmers, have been killed in land disputes in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> since 1980. Only three cases have been prosecuted, the organization says.
</TEXT>
