<HEAD>Government To Lengthen Military Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has lengthened its compulsory military service from 15 months to 18 months, a move the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> say could jeopardize East-West disarmament efforts. Following Tuesday's announcement by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, the Free Democrats, a minority party in Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s coalition government, also expressed reservations and asked that the move be delayed Given that about 400,000 more draft-age men than needed are now available, the opposition says extending service time is unnecessary. The Social Democrats also point to a lessened threat from the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. The armed forces now have about 495,000 members. Men aged 18 through 28 are subject to be drafted and about half of those in service are draftees.
