<HEAD>`Rain Man' and `Twins' Remain At Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Brotherly sagas `` Rain Man'' and `` Twins'' maintained the top two positions in box office receipts for the fifth consecutive weekend. `` Rain Man,'' starring <PERSON> Dustin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> as an autistic savant kidnapped by his brother, portrayed by <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruise </PERSON>, was No. 1 last weekend with $ 10.1 million in ticket sales. `` Twins,'' with <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVito </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzenegger </PERSON> as reunited twins who had been separated at birth, brought in $ 6.7 million. It was the third straight weekend that the films finished in that order. The previous two weekends, `` Twins'' finished ahead of `` Rain Man.'' `` Beaches,'' starring <PERSON> Better </PERSON> <PERSON> Midler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> as two women with an inseparable friendship, earned $ 5.1 million for third place last weekend as <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> widened its distribution. In fourth place was `` Accidental Tourist,'' earning $ 4.8 million, followed by `` Working Girl'' with $ 4.5 million. `` The Naked Gun: From the <ORGANIZATION> Files </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squad </ORGANIZATION>'' earned $ 4.4 million in its seventh week of release. `` Mississippi Burning,'' a fictionalized account of two <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents investigating the real slaying of three civil rights workers in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> during the 1960s, also went to wider distribution last weekend and took seventh place with just over $ 4 million. `` Deep Star Six,'' about a giant crab that devours undersea explorers, made a weak debut in eighth with $ 3.3 million. `` Dirty Rotten Scoundrels'' was next with just over $ 3 million and `` <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> and Co.'' with $ 1.9 million. No major releases were announced for this week, with theater owners anticipating the usual poor box office during Super Bowl weekend, said <ORGANIZATION> Exhibitor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Krier </PERSON>. Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in release. 1. `` Rain Man,'' <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION>, $ 10.1 million, 1,482 screens, $ 6,823 per screen, $ 69 million, five weeks. 2. `` Twins,'' Universal, $ 6.7 million, 1,630 screens, $ 4,140 per screen, $ 73.4 million, six weeks. 3. `` Beaches,'' <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>, $ 5.1 million, 706 screens, $ 7,309 per screen, $ 6.2 million, four weeks. 4. `` Accidental Tourist,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 4.8 million, 954 screens, $ 5,107 per screen, $ 13.4 million, four weeks. 5. `` Working Girl,'' 20th <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION>, $ 4.5 million, 1,140 screens, $ 3,960 per screen, $ 29.6 million, four weeks. 6. `` Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad,'' Paramount, $ 4.4 million, 1,765 screens, $ 2,494 per screen, $ 60.1 million, seven weeks. 7. `` Mississippi Burning,'' <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION>, $ 4 million, 551 screens, $ 7,417 per screen, $ 5.7 million, six weeks. 8. `` Deep Star Six,'' TriStar, $ 3.3 million, 1,117 screens, $ 2,960 per screen, $ 3.3 million, one week. 9. `` Dirty Rotten Scoundrels,'' <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION>, $ 3 million, 1,490 screens, $ 2,021 per screen, $ 31.1 million, five weeks. 10. `` <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.9 million, 1,410 screens, $ 1,360 per screen, $ 45.9 million, nine weeks.
