<HEAD>Time for Goodbyes for Reagan Veterans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Through her window, she can see the tourists on <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Avenue gawking through the wrought-iron fence at the White House. She can scan the stream of visitors arriving to see the president. She sits at the center of a universe of prime ministers, senators and heroic warriors who will headline the evening news. For only one more day, <PERSON> Leslye </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsht </PERSON> will sit in the little cubicle in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, dealing with the affairs of _ and sometimes speaking for _ the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Then, at the stroke of 12 on Friday, she turns in her pass and is out. `` There's life after the White House,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Arsht </PERSON>, her voice the least bit uncertain. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a company town if there ever was one, 4,307 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration jobs are up for grabs. Some who hold those jobs will stay where they are, but many more, like <PERSON> Leslye </PERSON> <PERSON> Arsht </PERSON>, find themselves on the job market. It is the friendliest of takeovers, this quadrennial rite, compared to the agony that occurs when a Democrat turns the White House over to a Republican, or vice versa. Not for 156 years has a president handed the reins to the man who served him as vice president. Yet, while the Bushites are n't exactly storming the gates, it's a traumatic time for many. As <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> flies off into the sunset, he leaves behind many loyal workers who wonder why they are suddenly out, while others stay on. The answer, of course, is that people work hard in a campaign, and the jobs that serve as rewards are in great demand. `` We had our turn; now it's their turn,'' says Ms. <PERSON> Arsht </PERSON>, who came from the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> two years ago with <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> when he became <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s spokesman. She has been deputy press secretary, a job that will go to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. `` I'm a Texan, a lifetime supporter of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' she says. `` It's a bittersweet time.'' Outside her door in the White House press office is a huge box being filled with files for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>. The work of the press office goes on, but it's obvious that things are being readied for the big change. On Friday, the rooms will be mostly empty, the cupboards bare, the walls nude. It wo n't be as stark as, say, when <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> left town eight years ago, because <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> will stay on to serve <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as chief spokesman. In one part of the office, a cardboard box is marked `` Do not throw away. This is not trash.'' In the hallway, a photo gallery that has been dominated by pictures of <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has undergone a subtle turn: The pictures of the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> have been augmented by photos of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. One of those who is leaving is <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerrard </PERSON>, the closest thing the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has to an institutional memory. Ms. <PERSON> Gerrard </PERSON> came into the White House 25 years ago with <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, as a fresh-from-college secretary after the assassination of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. She has stayed, serving as the press secretary's secretary, through <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and she is ready to live a life without the endless workdays and the constant crises. `` I now want to be able to control my own schedule,'' she says. She knows what the incoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> staffers will soon learn, that `` in the press office, you have to hit the ground running. There is nothing to prepare you for what you find when you get here.'' Indeed, reporters were pressing <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> on Tuesday about where they will get information after noon on Friday. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> and <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> will be the only veteran hands remaining in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. The rest of the press office staff will come from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> team. Many of them will see the inside of the office for the first time when they come to work on inauguration day. `` It's a matter of sensitivity,'' <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> says. `` Nobody wants to have the new person watching over their shoulder.'' Many of the people leaving spent the weekend packing their own belongings. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, too, was seen by <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> last week putting some things into a box. `` The president and first lady have been packing for some time,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` They have shipped most of their private goods to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> already.'''
