<HEAD>Soviets, Chinese Make US Wheat Purchase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Private exporters have new orders for 530,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and 200,000 metric tons from the Chinese under the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> program that lets them buy grain at cut-rate prices. The wheat sold to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> by private exporters was part of 2 million tons authorized Dec. 23 under the department's Export Enhancement Program, or <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. The wheat was bought under a long-term supply agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, now in its sixth year. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the wheat is for shipment in January, February and March. Counting some wheat left over from previous EEP arrangements, the Soviets have 670,200 tons still available under the program. The Chinese, however, have used almost all of their current subsidy authorization. In the past, each country has had new authorizations set by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> after exhausting what was available. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> bought more than 9 million tons of wheat under <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangements during the fifth year of the grain agreement. The pact expired last Sept. 30 but was later extended through Dec. 31, 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangement allows exporters to sell wheat and other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies. Last year, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> totaled slightly less than 5.2 million tons. Wheat sales in 1987-88, all subsidized, totaled slightly more than 9 million tons. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 530,000 tons of wheat would be about 19.5 million bushels. Wheat prices at the farm have been averaging more than $ 4 per bushel, according to recent <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> market figures, making the new sale worth an estimated $ 78 million. Besides the wheat for 1988-89 delivery under the pact, the Soviets have ordered 10.2 million tons of corn, 450,000 tons of soybeans, and 1,132,500 tons of soybean meal, plus 500,000 tons of grain sorghum. Only the wheat is subsidized. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the wheat sales will carry an average subsidy rate of $ 23.35 per ton, or about 64 cents per bushel. He said the bonuses on the 530,000 tons of wheat will be paid to eight companies: <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 80,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 200,000; <ORGANIZATION> Garnac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000; <ORGANIZATION> Richco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000; <ORGANIZATION> Tradigrain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000; <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 25,000; <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 25,000; and <ORGANIZATION> Bunge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000. In the case of the 200,000 tons sold to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the wheat was part of 1 million tons authorized Dec. 30 for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The wheat sales were handled by two companies: <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 115,000 tons, and <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 85,000 tons. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the wheat was sold for March shipment and will carry an average subsidy rate of $ 22.49 per ton, or about 62 cents per bushel. Only 10,000 tons remain available to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> under the program, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says that for the first time it will reserve some of its summer jobs for students from 17 historically black universities. Deputy Secretary <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said Tuesday that 563 of the 1989 summer jobs will be held aside as part of the department's effort `` to increase the number of minority students in agriculture, forestry and home economics.'' Last year 17,753 students nationwide worked during the summer months for various <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agencies, and officials said they expect about that many this year. The 563 jobs reserved for the black schools would represent about 3 percent of the total. `` Agriculture is more than crop and livestock production,'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. `` Animal and plant sciences, economics, forestry, marketing and computer technology are just some of the varied career fields in agriculture today.'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said the jobs will be with 19 <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agencies and will be located nationwide. He said interested students at 17 institutions should contact university placement offices before March 1. The universities, collectively known as 1890 institutions because of land-grant legislation that year, are being targeted in other ways by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. On Dec. 29, the department announced it is establishing offices at each of the 17 schools to help encourage more minorities in agriculture. Also, on Jan. 9, the proposed <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> budget for next year included $ 80.2 million for new and expanded programs to increase the teaching, recruitment and research capabilities at the 1890 schools, a 20 percent increase from the current level. The 17 schools are: <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> A & amp; M, <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Alcorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Lorman </LOCATION>, Miss. <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION>, Pine Bluff. <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Frankfort </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Langston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Langston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland-Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shore </ORGANIZATION>, Princess <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>. Prairie View A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, Prairie View, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATI