<HEAD>Moiseyev Dance Company Opens at Radio City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Moiseyev </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, visiting <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for the eighth time since 1958, proves it can still surprise. Dancing briskly with their knees bent in an impossible squat, vaulting high in the air, these Soviet dancers are astonishingly athletic and virtuosic, and they look like they're really having fun. The audience picks up on that and has fun, too. The company opened at <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> for 14 performances on Tuesday. They look splendid on that tall, wide stage. There are old favorites on the bill, but <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Moiseyev </PERSON>, 83, who founded the company in 1937, has choreographed some new things as well. This is good for viewers who've seen the company before. `` Partisans,'' in which dancers in long cloaks glide as though on rollers, then break into horse-like gaits, will always look remarkable, no matter how often seen. A new one on this tour is `` <PERSON> Aragonnaise </PERSON> <PERSON> Jota </PERSON>,'' based on Spanish dance. It's brief and beautiful, the men in white and black, the women in white blouses, red skirts and black lace aprons. Another new one to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is `` Malamba,'' which <PERSON> Moiseyev </PERSON> built using Argentine dances. Also on Tuesday's program was `` Polovtsian Dances,'' from 1974, set to <PERSON> Borodin </PERSON> music known here primarily from `` Kismet.'' The Khan reviews his warriors and captive women. The women are in harem dress and <PERSON> Moiseyev </PERSON> has managed to make their dancing exotic and not at all sexy. It's a long dance with a string of solos and small dances for various ensembles. It would be too lavish for a classical ballet but in this gravity-defying style it seemed an admirable production number. Farcical timing is all in `` Sanchakou,'' in which two Chinese men have a swordfight in the dark. At the beginning, when one puts out his candle, the spotlight gets smaller. It gives the illusion they're in the dark but lets the audience see every near slice. The tour began last week in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and went to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> before coming to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. From Jan. 31 through March 20, the <PERSON> Moiseyev </PERSON> will perform in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Clearwater </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cupertino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.
