<FIRST>r w PM-WorldGrain     01-18 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Grain,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Countries Making Hay with Grain Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wheat supply crunch in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is helping the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> export surplus grain at record levels and fat prices, according to <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysts. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that `` limited southern hemisphere exportable supplies'' of wheat, coupled with a tight inventory in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, is behind the surge in EEC exports. According to the agency's report, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> will export a record 19 million metric tons of wheat in the international trading year that runs through June, up from 15.3 million tons in 1987-88. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat exports were projected at 40.9 million tons, down from 43.4 million tons in 1987-88. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s exports were shown at 11.7 million tons, down from 23.6 million last year. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> also showed declines. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. It said the 1989 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> winter wheat crop, for harvest this coming summer, `` will be the first new-crop supplies available for export and, given the nature of the world wheat market, the size and quality of this crop will likely set the stage for prices in 1989-90.'' The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> reported last week that American farmers had boosted plantings of winter wheat for this year's harvest by 12 percent. However, much of the newly planted crop is in need of moisture. `` Wheat prices continue to strengthen and have reached their highest level since January 1982 amid a flurry of recent purchases and early concerns about the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> wheat crop,'' the report said. The global wheat stockpile by this summer is expected to shrink to 115.3 million tons from 145.6 million tons a year ago, the report said. Foreign supplies were projected at 100.8 million tons, compared with 14.5 million tons in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Last summer the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share of the wheat inventory was 34.3 million tons and the remainder of the world, 111.3 million tons.
</TEXT>
