<HEAD>Civil Rights Group Urges Bush to Toughen Enforcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should set tough civil rights enforcement as a major goal of his administration, a 17-member panel of former federal officials says. `` There is a major rebuilding job to be done to reconstruct the machinery of enforcing civil rights,'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said at a news conference called by the <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. The private group released a 37-page report titled `` One Nation, Indivisible: The Civil Rights Challenge for the 1990s,'' which offered evidence of a falloff in civil rights enforcement in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> era. It said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has filed 31 cases to challenge discriminatory voting practices since 1981. Panel members called that a sharp drop from the record of earlier administrations. The report also said enforcement of equal employment rules applying to federal contractors declined from 269 cases in 1980 to 22 cases in 1986. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> estimates that 2 million cases of housing bias occur each year, but an average of 10 housing discrimination cases have been filed annually, the report said. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said that number represented about half the level under the administrations of former presidents <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON> criticized the notion that there has been a slowdown. He cited a victory in a key housing bias case in <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, as well as a major voting rights case pending against <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> and a lawsuit filed two months ago to bar alleged hiring discrimination by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s police hiring system. `` We've taken heat for these things but we've continued to enforce the laws strenuously,'' he said. He said he could not readily verify that the eight-year total of voting rights cases was 31. But he did say that because court actions under previous administrations remain in place `` the number by definition gets smaller.'' As for cases involving federal contractors, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has no authority to initiate suits and merely acts on matters referred to it by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Flemming </PERSON>, chairman of the commission, said the group was sending its report to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` in the hope that he can turn around the'80s as far as civil rights enforcement is concerned.''
