<HEAD>Soft-Pedaling Increases Won't Fool Public, Bush Adviser Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The public is likely to view higher levies on gasoline, alcohol and tobacco as tax increases, even if politicians try to soft-pedal them by calling them `` user fees,'' President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s incoming budget director says. The comments by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> shed light on the thinking of the new administration and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who campaigned on a pledge of no new taxes. Lawmakers and others in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> have been closely watching the words of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his aides to see if the vice president backs off his campaign promise. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> submitted written answers to questions posed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which holds confirmation hearings Thursday on his appointment. The questionnaire and responses were obtained Tuesday from a source who asked to not be identified. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, who has been tapped as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, said that `` depending on the application of funds,'' taxes on gasoline, tobacco and alcohol might be called user fees. But he added, `` the public, however, tends to see these rather unequivocally as taxes.'' He said fees for government services are not a tax `` as long as the government is directly charging the beneficiary only for the cost of the service provided by the government.'' He also said eliminating the deduction for interest on certain types of borrowing and taxing employer-provided fringe benefits could be considered `` definitional changes.'' `` One could engage in long discussions of when one or another revenue measure is or is not a tax,'' <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> wrote. `` Putting academics and sophistry aside, however, my suspicion is that in the end such definitional matters are political: applying the old if-it-looks-like-a-duck rule, if it looks like a tax to most Americans, it's a tax.'' Many congressional Democrats have said they do not understand how the fiscal 1990 deficit can be reduced to $ 100 billion, as required by the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law, without new taxes. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., asked Tuesday about <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>'s comments on taxes, said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was never tagged as a taxer, even though he signed 11 tax increases into law `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may find he wants to try to follow in that tradition, but one thing should be clear: We in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> stand ready to work with the administration to deal with these massive deficits, regardless of semantics, and we look forward to a budget proposal from <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' he said in a written statement. <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., also discussed budget matters Tuesday, indicating that the $ 13 billion in new revenues contained in the spending plan <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> submitted last week might be a good starting point for negotiations between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` If the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> number is used, which is $ 13 billion, then obviously that gives us the opportunity to look not only at those that were suggested by the administration, but other areas as well in order to meet that number,'' <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> told members of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> said the revenue raisers proposed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, along with excise taxes on items such as energy, `` are worthy of consideration.'' In his budget, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed raising new money by selling federal assets, imposing or increasing user fees, repealing a reduction in aviation taxes, and other measures.
