<HEAD>Loophole Open for $39 Million in House Campaign Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A select group of 190 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members stockpiled $ 39.2 million in campaign money that can be converted to their personal use under a loophole in election laws, a non-profit group says. Public Citizen's <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> noted Tuesday that the select group is covered by a special provision in federal law permitting those who were serving in the House on Jan. 8, 1980, to keep any remaining campaign funds. The report also said the members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> elected to the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have built combined campaign war chests of $ 67 million. Public Citizen is a research, lobbying and litigation group founded by consumer advocate <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> in 1971. Its report blamed the surplus campaign chests for the 98 percent success rate among <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> incumbents running in 1988 and 1986, adding, `` There is a greater turnover in the Supreme Soviet than in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> House of Representatives.'' `` This certainly discourages qualified candidates from challenging the financially stronger representatives and further ensures the ` incumbent lock' on the House.'' The report covered the period from Jan. 1, 1987, through Nov. 28, 1988. The $ 67 million in surplus money averages $ 154,000 per member, up 39 percent from the 1985-86 balance of $ 48.4 million _ an average of $ 111,332. The $ 39.2 million stockpiled by 189 current members and the late Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, D-Ala., for possible personal use is a 34 percent increase from the amount on hand in January 1987 Those who can take advantage of the loophole can watch their money grow `` until they retire,'' the report said. The money `` can be transferred to other political races, donated to their favorite charities -LRB- while writing off the tax deduction -RRB-, used to buy a new car or pay for that needed vacation,'' according to the report. The report said Reps. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreier </PERSON>, R-Calif., <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., each have more than $ 1 million stockpiled, with <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> permitted to convert the money to personal After surveying how former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members used the money, the report said that Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, spent $ 386,064 in leftover campaign funds on legal expenses related to his criminal convictions. He was found guilty of accepting an illegal gratuity and obstruction of justice in accepting a paid <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> vacation from a former <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> Democratic leader; and of racketeering and accepting bribes from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in exchange for his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> influence. The late Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, left $ 310,000 to his wife, and the late Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, R-Tenn., left more than $ 600,000 to his family, the report said
