<HEAD>Suicides, Other Unnatural Deaths On The Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Suicides and other unnatural deaths have increased by 50 percent during the 1980s, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said today. A survey of 10 million people in 25 locales found that the death rate from unnatural causes increased from 31 per 100,000 people in 1981 to 47 in 1987. Four-fifths of the deaths came by suicide, drowning, poisoning and traffic accidents, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said. The report did not say if murder was included in the statistics. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> gives no statistics on suicide, but <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said that in the countryside, where most Chinese live, one-third of unnatural deaths were by suicide. More women than men took their own lives, it said. The survey found that family disputes, marital problems and poor personal relations led to half the suicides. About 20 percent of suicides were terminally ill patients. The report said two-thirds of those killing themselves used poison, and called for tighter control over dispensing of poisons. Tens of thousands of Chinese are believed to have killed themselves during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution when ultra-leftists persecuted huge numbers of people. Today, most suicides are linked to personal problems and difficulties in adjusting to social changes as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> switches to a more market-oriented, competitive economic system. Last year, the nation's first non-governmental suicide prevention center was established in <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>.
