<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Artists such as <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Stella </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON> mingled with congressmen, bureaucrats, judges, patrons, diplomats and other dignitaries at a pre-inaugural party marking the 10th anniversary of the National Gallery of Art's East Building. More than 1,000 people attended the black-tie event Tuesday night, including I.M. <PERSON> Pei </PERSON>, the architect who designed the East Building at the foot of <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>; art collector <PERSON> Estee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauder </PERSON>; Sen. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>, D-Va.; and <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>, nominated by President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to be <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative Touring the gallery's newly mounted exhibition of 20th Century paintings, drawings and sculpture on three floors of the East Building, <PERSON> Stella </PERSON> predicted that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will continue government support for the arts, though without any `` great outpouring'' of federal assistance. `` The emphasis will be on the performing arts,'' said <PERSON> Stella </PERSON>, waving a cigar under one of the giant canvases. `` He wo n't be interested in supporting the avant garde. The government's job is to take care of the majority.'' `` They do n't need to take care of those who can take care of themselves,'' said <PERSON> Stella </PERSON>, known for his minimalist paintings on different shaped canvases. `` We're not charity cases.'' <PERSON> Stella </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON> agreed that the healthy economy favors artists by spurring purchase of their works as financial investments and additions to private collections. `` The art