<HEAD>Rates On Short-Term Securities Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities fell in the latest auction. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.2 billion in three-month bills Tuesday at an average discount rate of 8.30 percent, down from 8.36 percent last week. Another $ 7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.35 percent, down from 8.48 percent last week. The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 8.24 percent on Jan. 3, and six-month bills averaged 8.33 percent on Dec. 27. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 8.60 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,790.20 and and 8.84 percent for six-month bills selling for $ 9,577.90. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said that the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, fell to 9.11 percent last week after averaging 9.17 percent the week before.
