<HEAD>Report Says Britain One Of Europe's Filthiest Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has become one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s filthiest nations, its city streets a jungle of garbage and graffiti, the government-funded <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said in a report today. `` <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> is filthy, worse than comparable cities in mainland <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' says the report, which blames the problem on a growing lack of personal discipline. `` The same is true of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as a whole, as children chuck away sweet -LRB- candy -RRB- wrappers and ice lolly wrappings, and adults calmly wind down car windows and dispatch empty cans as well as squashed paper packets as they speed to their presumably well-kept homes or places of work,'' it says. The author, commission urban affairs specialist <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hillman </PERSON>, said that although the report, entitled `` A New Look for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>,'' concentrates on the capital, the problems affect all of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The report describes street gutters filled with empty beverage cans and old newspapers; plastic garbage sacks dumped around lampposts, often spilling their contents on to the sidewalk; and roadsides lined with discarded mattresses, broken chairs, old stoves, abandoned supermarket carts and other trash. Other complaints were of overflowing litter bins; remains of fast-food meals strewn around shopping malls; and dog and pigeon excrement on sidewalks and in public parks. The report also noted graffiti on trains, the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> subway, buses and in `` ill-designed areas of urban residential wilderness and almost any convenient blank stone or painted wall.'' It said people increasingly `` graze'' in and around shopping malls, eating on the move and dropping food and wrappers on the way. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, in a foreword to the report, wrote of the need for residents of all the country's municipalities to `` involve themselves in the upkeep and improvement of their local streets and centers.'' The report recommends that the banks of the <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thames </LOCATION> be turned into a national park. Legislation covering officially designated national parks imposes rigorous controls on the collection of garbage and similar matters. In July 1986, government ministers and pop music entrepreneur <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Branson </PERSON> launched a $ 40 million drive using taxpayers' money to clean up <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s streets, countryside and derelict industrial land. But Londoners and foreign visitors say there has been little evidence that the project has had much effect. The <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> was first set up in 1924 to advise government departments on projects and developments affecting national or public amenities.
