 Sikh militants raided a village in northern <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> and shot and killed a Hindu family of four, police said today. About five Sikh gunmen raided the home of Anant Ram in <LOCATION> Bhurhe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gill </LOCATION>, 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, at midnight Tuesday and killed four members of his family, police chief G.S. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said. Ram and his two sons were killed inside a room and the assailants shot and killed <PERSON> Vinod </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON>, a relative of Ram, when tried to resist the attack, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said. Sikhs, who make up two percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people, allege they are discriminated against by the Hindus, at 80 percent of the populace the country's religious majority. Sikhs are, however, in majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, a rich farming state bordering <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Sikh militants have been campaigning since 1982 for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The latest slayings brought the death toll blamed on the militants this year to 120. Last year 2,400 deaths were blamed on the militants.
