<FIRST>r i China-HumanRights     01-18 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>China-Human Rights,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Acknowledges Torture And Other Rights Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State agencies last year investigated more than 11,000 cases of human rights violations in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, including torture, illegal arrests and unwarranted search and seizure, the nation's leading newspaper reported today In an unusual report, the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said more than 50 high-ranking officials, 2,600 government workers, including policemen, and 1,250 employees of collective enterprises committed such violations. The story cited an example of Officer <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiugang </PERSON>, a policeman from <LOCATION> Hengyang </LOCATION>, a city in <LOCATION> Hunan </LOCATION> province, who took bribes to have criminals released from jail. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> province nine times and secured the release of 36 prisoners using bogus letters of introduction, the paper said. For his services, he was bribed $ 1,784 _ or about 50 times the average Chinese police officer's monthly salary, the paper said. Last year, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> was arrested and sentenced to 10 years in jail. The report said that of the 11,300 cases investigated last year, 4,454 involved wrongful charges, forced confessions, torture, illegal arrests and unwarranted search and seizure. Other cases concerned dereliction of duty and using one's office for profit, it said. One of the cases cited was a fire in <LOCATION> Daxinganling </LOCATION> in northeastern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in May 1987 which left 193 people dead and millions of acres burned. In all, 11 people were sentenced to prison terms for dereliction of duty. One official involved ordered fire trucks to protect his own house while the fire ravaged an oil depot and a grain warehouse, the report said. Another official, at the time the head of a fire prevention bureau, fled the fire on a motorcycle, it said. The article was unusual in that it openly mentioned torture, forced confessions and illegal search and seizure. It also acknowledged that many of the cases were difficult to crack because `` those prosecuted were government workers.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has acknowledged that torture and other breaches of human rights were frequent during the 10-year ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution that ended in 1976. Little criticism has since been tolerated of the state's internal security bureaus, though lawyers say several Chinese have recently sued the police for wrongful arrest and won. Later this year, the government is expected to come out with legislation allowing citizens to sue other government bureaus. Chinese lawyers say they are working to raise people's consciousness of their rights Recent cases, such as that of two models who sued the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, are being widely publicized to teach people about invasion of privacy and other rights. The models are suing because they said the academy used pictures of them in an exhibition of nudes without asking their permission. The case has yet to be decided. Discussion of rights breaks down, however, when political freedoms are raised. The government clearly states that no criticism of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> or socialism is allowed. `` We are trying to set a foundation,'' said one lawyer in a recent interview. `` It would be asking too much for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to grant political freedoms at this point.''
