ty Relations Board said the warning signs of this week's violence were apparent. He said his group keeps a weekly `` tension chart'' and had voiced alarm in recent weeks when it saw levels similar to 1980 and 1982. But, as in the past, perceptions of violence likely will linger after the violence subsides. `` This really puts a damper on literally hundreds of thousands of volunteer hours that have been put in by this community preparing for the -LRB- Sunday's -RRB- Super Bowl,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Beacon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which promotes <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. `` It's not that we have things that are any different from other urban areas; it's just that the timing of how they occur is absolutely incredible,'' he added. `` An incident like this you do n't ever want to happen, but it's just doubly unfortunate that it happens this week. <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> sports writer <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Buck </PERSON>, whose car windshield was shattered in Monday night's violence, said publicity about the violence will cancel out <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s hospitality this week. `` Unfortunately, I think a lot of good effort was ruined in one short three - or four-hour period,'' he said `` A year of hard work went down the drain.''
