<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury may convict <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> of beating his illegally adopted daughter to death even if they find he did not strike the fatal blow, the trial judge said. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> said Tuesday if the jurors find <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> was aware the child was injured and in danger, and that she died as a result of action or inaction by him, then they may convict him of murder. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, 47, a disbarred millionaire lawyer, is charged with second-degree murder in the beating death of 6-year-old <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, the girl he illegally obtained at birth from an unwed teen and raised as his own. The child was removed unconscious from his <ORGANIZATION> Greenwich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Village </ORGANIZATION> apartment on Nov. 2, 1987. She died of a brain injury three days later at a nearby hospital. The prosecution charges <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> hit the girl, but even if he killed her unintentionally, he acted `` recklessly'' and showed a `` depraved indifference'' to her life by allowing her to lie unconscious for 12 hours without seeking help. The judge said he will submit for the jury's consideration the four homicide counts available in this state. They are second-degree murder, first-and second-degree manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide. The judge denied defense motions to throw out the homicide charges saying there was `` sufficient evidence'' to sustain them. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> DiLuzio </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> to drop the charges on the ground that the only evidence implicating <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> in the child's death came from an accomplice, <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s former live-in companion `` I will charge that <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> is an accomplice as a matter of law'' in the death of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> said. This means the panel may consider her testimony only if there is corroborating _ supporting _ evidence. `` It seems to me there is ample corroboration of the accomplice testimony in this case,'' the judge said, `` and the motion to dismiss those counts on that ground will be denied.'' <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> granted a defense motion to drop the endangering the welfare of a child charge with respect to <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. `` I'm disinclined to submit that count to the jury,'' he said. He called the charge a `` distraction'' and said <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> has already served more than the one-year maximum for that count anyway since he has been held without bail since November 1987. The prosecution and defense have rested in the case and the defense is expected to give closing arguments on Thursday. The prosecution will sum up on Friday and <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> will give his final instructions to the jurors on Monday just before they begin deliberating. <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> cautioned <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s lawyers against saying anything in summation that sounds like an insanity defense. `` You can call it insanity or you can call it vanilla,'' <PERSON> Rothwax </PERSON> said, warning that he will reopen the trial, now in its 12th week, and allow the prosecution psychiatrist to testify about his interviews last week with <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> if defense lawyers say anything that smacks of an insanity defense. `` We have no intention of arguing insanity,'' <PERSON> DiLuzio </PERSON> said. The judge also said he will tell the jurors that he allowed them to see and hear evidence that Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, 46, a former children's book editor, was battered by <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> only so they could assess her state of mind at the time of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s death and evaluate her testimony accordingly
