<HEAD>Association Reports Record Number of Closings in 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A record number of community hospitals closed for the sixth year in a row last year, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said, promising to fight any further cuts in federal <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid funding. Eighty-one hospitals in 28 states shut down in 1988, the organization said Tuesday. The <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> was hardest hit, with 18 closings in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> alone. In addition, 21 non-community hospitals closed in 15 states, the association said. Community hospitals are generally defined as those not serving a specific group like a university, military base or prison. They can be publicly or privately owned. Non-community hospitals typically provide rehabilitative or long-term care. The closings were primarily due to inadequate Medicare and Medicaid payments for treatment of the elderly and poor, said association President <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>. `` Hospitals can not lose money or barely break even year after year and remain open,'' Ms. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said. `` It's just that simple.'' She said the association would `` pull out all the stops'' to stop cuts in <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and improve health care funding for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s indigent Since 1980, 445 community hospitals have closed, and the number has increased steadily since 1982, the association said. Forty-three of the 81 community hospitals that closed in 1988 were rural. `` For the last several years, seven out of 10 rural hospitals and 50 percent of urban hospitals have lost money caring for patients,'' Ms. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said. For most hospitals, profit margins are disappearing, and they can not cut costs to stay open, said association vice president <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. `` The problem is not excess expenses,'' <PERSON> William