<ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> had not yet compiled all the reports from airlines. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, responding to another <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> order covering fire sprinkler systems in <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757 cargo holds, said Tuesday it found faulty wiring in two of its aircraft. That brings to seven the total number of 757s found with such problems worldwide. One case of faulty wiring in a 757 was reported to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> in August by <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brunei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> relayed the information to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> only this month, <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> of the agency's <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> office told the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Intelligencer </ORGANIZATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> is under an obligation to look into these types of things and report them to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` There's some leeway in the process, but if there is a long delay that would be a concern to us. The reporting delay was a `` blip,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiminez </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was a breakdown in communication. Generally -LRB- both manufacturer and carrier -RRB- report to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, but in this case it just did n't happen. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> orders cover only domestic airliners, but foreign carriers using <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> built aircraft generally comply with any safety inspections ordered. `` We're looking to see what happened in the system to allow this -LRB- faulty wiring -RRB- to happen, where it happened, how it happened, and to see how we can make it not happen again,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said officials would not take any steps affecting production of new 757s until they received the results of the inspections from the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> orders covering 737s and 757s were not related, except that they both involved cross-wiring. The cargo-hold problems have been reported in another Delta-operated 757, one belonging to <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brunei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, two owned by <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holland </ORGANIZATION>, and one operated by the British airline Air 2000. One of the Air Holland planes was being used by a charter company in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which operates 25 of the 757s; <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, which has 33; and <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION>, which has seven, said Tuesday that they found no problems with any of their planes. No other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline operates the 757. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said the carrier immediately notified the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> of the latest two cases and corrected the problems which would have prevented sprinklers from working properly in the event of a fire in a baggage hold. One airplane had a crossed-wiring problem that would have turned on the wrong sprinklers if a fire had broken out, <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON> said. The other had faulty wiring that would have warned the pilot of a fire but would not have activated the sprinklers, he said. He said it was a similar crossed-wiring problem found on a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> plane before delivery from the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> factory that prompted the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> 757 airworthiness directive last week. Airlines had until Tuesday morning to complete the inspections and regular airline service was not affected, officials said.
