up 6th pvs, ```Bodies were ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of people rushed to hospitals in southern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> today, hoping to find that loved ones had survived a train-bus collision in which at least 45 people were killed, officials said. Most of the dead were schoolchildren. Police and witnesses to Tuesday's crash said the bus driver apparently thought he could beat the express train, but his vehicle's engine stalled on the unguarded crossing about 43 miles south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. At a Cabinet meeting today, President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> ordered all the country's 758 railway crossings to have gates installed by Monday, said spokesman <PERSON> Festus </PERSON> <PERSON> Perera </PERSON>. Seventy-one of the 120 mostly young people on the bus were injured, and six critically injured victims were taken to <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> today for emergency surgery, police said. No one on the train was injured. The train, traveling at about 40 mph, knocked the bus about 150 feet down the track, witnesses said, and many bus passengers were hurled into a field. Others, most of them aged 5 to 15, were trapped inside the mangled vehicle. `` Bodies were all over ... Children were screaming,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> priest who helped carry the injured to ambulances. Many of the victims could not easily be identified, and nurses asked relatives to check clothing for identification. At the crash site, police searched through bloodstained school books, pencils and shoes for clues to the victims' identities. `` We are working with badly mutilated bodies, some of them only limbs,'' said one police officer. Relatives crowded into the two government-run hospitals where the dead and injured were taken. One wailing mother walked through the hospital halls calling out, `` Inoka, <LOCATION> Inoka </LOCATION>.'' Nurses ran after her and stopped her from entering the morgue. <PERSON> Hema </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>, the president's wife, visited the accident site and hospitals this morning, going from bed to bed trying to comfort the injured and console relatives of the dead. The bus had picked up children from four schools in <LOCATION> Amblangoda </LOCATION> and was headed toward <LOCATION> Urgasmanhandiya </LOCATION>, about 10 miles away, when the crash occurred. One witness said she tried to flag the bus down because she thought the driver probably could not see the train because of a light drizzle. But other witnesses and police said they thought the driver saw the train and still tried to make it across the track, especially since five children riding on the steps of the bus jumped out and escaped injury. The bus driver suffered minor injuries, they said.
