<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Jaromir </PERSON> <PERSON> Johanes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> today dismissed harsh Western criticism of a police crackdown on dissidents in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and said the demonstrators had broken the law by assembling. `` Anyone in this hall who wants to point the finger at other nations, including <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, should first of all look at himself,'' <PERSON> Johanes </PERSON> said. `` Acts in breach of legal and public order can not be tolerated by any government,'' he said, departing from his prepared text. `` Laws have to be observed by all.'' Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, meanwhile, said upon arriving in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> that the Berlin Wall is not a subject for negotiations at the conference in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> on human rights and <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> relations. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, scheduled to address the final session of the 35-nation conference on Thursday, also told reporters there are `` many areas in which -LRB- East and West -RRB- just disagree'' on human rights issues. <PERSON> Johanes </PERSON> spoke a day after police armed with truncheons broke up crowds of protesters in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> for a third day, chasing hundreds of youths with water cannons. On Sunday, police used tear gas, batons, dogs and water cannons to break up 5,000 demonstrators gathered to remember <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Palach </PERSON>, a Czech student who killed himself in 1969 to protest the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of his homeland. On Monday, 14 prominent dissidents including banned playwright <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> were detained after they tried to lay flowers in <PERSON> Palach </PERSON>'s memory. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, Charter 77 spokespersons <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PE