s. We shall expect similar moves by other states,'' he added. <PERSON> Johanes </PERSON> made no such pledge to review Czechoslovak laws, thus emphasizing the gap that opened up at the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> conference between reformist nations in the Soviet bloc and those more reluctant to change. The accords call for new arms control talks between <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact to reduce conventional arms across <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Those negotiations are due to open in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> March 9. <PERSON> Johanes </PERSON> said the new talks `` will become an important practical test of the political resolve to reach tangible progress'' toward disarmament. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> was asked by reporters if the recently concluded agreement at the conference indicated the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall could now be dismantled. `` I do n't think that the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall is a subject for the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting,'' he said. `` Each state has the right to build its frontiers as it wishes and we must proceeed from there.''
