<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist leaders passed a resolution early today that could restore Solidarity's legal status, but officials of the banned trade union movement said too many unacceptable conditions appeared to be attached. Among conditions set before today's vote by the party's governing <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was that Solidarity declare itself in favor of socialism, promise no strikes for two years and forfeit financial assistance from the West. There was no immediate comment from Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. An aide said he would hold a news conference Thursday. Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> said during debate Tuesday he favored ending the seven-year ban on Solidarity if its leaders promised not to drag the economically depressed country `` into anarchy.'' The official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said today a majority of the 230-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> had approved the party leadership's stand on trade union and political pluralism Other details of the proposal, debated 17 hours until 3 a.m., were not immediately available. The vote occurred too late to be included in morning newspapers and the text was not immediately carried by <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also gave an overwhelming vote of confidence to top party authorities led by First Secretary <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> reported unanimous approval with four abstentions. A Solidarity source in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>'s proposal to reinstate the only independent labor movement ever allowed in the Soviet bloc appeared at first glance unclear, `` unacceptable'' or even `` laughable.'' The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Solidarity could not function as a free trade union if forced to embrace an ideology and stripped of the right to strike. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> said the government needed assurances that a legally functioning Solidarity would differ from the movement that used general strike threats as a pressure tactic during its 16-month heyday, which began in 1980. The organization was outlawed in 1982. Solidarity activists on Tuesday welcomed the shift in the party's stance but said they must proceed with caution, because authorities had acted out of necessity rather than good will `` The authorities will do whatever that have to do to stay on top. Let's wait and see what they have to say and read the fine print carefully,'' said <PERSON> Maciej </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>, a Solidarity leader at <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> crushed Solidarity in a December 1981 military crackdown, interning thousands of activists and banning the movement the next year. After a series of spring and summer strikes demanding higher pay and Solidarity's reinstatement, <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> agreed to resume contacts with the movement. However, promised negotiations with the opposition were repeatedly delayed over conditions set by both sides. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has warned that the public mood is reaching the boiling point because of rising prices and annoying consumer shortages. In the latest sign of tension, a strike for higher pay and legalization of Solidarity on Tuesday shut down the 1,100-worker Pabianice Fabric Works in the textile city of <LOCATION> Lodz </LOCATION>. Under the proposal <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> put to the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, final legalization of Solidarity would follow a two-year probationary period lasting until May 3, 1991, the 200th anniversary of the adoption of a progressive constitution that Imperial <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> quickly invalidated by force. `` We have to gain certainty that this Solidarity, which can not be a simple repetition of the old one, does not pull the country into anarchy,'' <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> addressed specific questions to Solidarity in his speech, saying the answers would determine if the union could be a partner, or whether it would remain a `` political opponent.'' He asked what position Solidarity would take toward anti-communist Polish groups like the Confederation for an Independent <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and whether it would continue to take money from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and other foreign organizations. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has granted Solidarity $ 1 million a year the last two years, but Polish authorities have held up spending of half of this. Total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to Solidarity was estimated last year at $ 5 million by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. Solidarity does not deny receiving foreign help. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he would take money from the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> if he could use it to defend trade union freedoms. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> stressed that the economy would be the most important factor for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during the next few years. `` It above all needs order and peace,'' he said. `` Even the best administration methods and solutions will not meet our hopes if the ... economy becomes a field of political struggles.''
