<HEAD>Psychiatrists: Confessed TWA Hijacker Mentally Competent for Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Psychiatric experts said today that confessed hijacker <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> is mentally competent to stand trial, despite head wounds he received during fighting in his native <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> is charged with air piracy and murder in the June 14, 1985 hijacking of a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> jetliner in which <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was slain. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> admitted taking part in the hijacking but denied killing <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>. Following the seizure of the Athens-to-Rome flight, 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days. The <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> court, acting on a defense request in November, ordered psychiatric tests for <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> after it was revealed in court testimony that he had received head wounds in fighting in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, where a civil war has raged for 13 years. <PERSON> Willi </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hasso </PERSON> <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, professors of psychiatry at <ORGANIZATION> Giessen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, 35 miles north of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, testified today on the results of their tests of <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s mental processes `` are quick, coherent, and concise.'' His head has some scars, but `` none of them is sensitive to outside pressure,'' <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> said. He said the defendant's reflexes were normal and that <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> had no coordination problems. `` Mr. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> is in all respects mentally fit,'' <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said he tested <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> for mental disturbances, intellectual development and concentration. He described the defendant as `` orderly thinking, and stable.'' `` He was friendly, courteous, cooperative, absolutely not withdrawn,'' <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said his tests showed <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was of average intelligence and that `` cerebal damage could not be established, indicating a fully healthy brain.'' Following the psychiatrists' testimony, the defense asked that <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> be given additional tests. Chief Judge <PERSON> Heiner </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueckenberger </PERSON> did not immediately rule on the request. The trial, which began July 5, resumed this week after a break of nearly one month. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> has been kept in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s Preungesheim prison since his arrest at the city's airport Jan. 23, 1987. He was arrested after being caught with liquid explosives in his luggage. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> requested his extradition, but following the kidnapping of two West Germans in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> said he would be tried here instead. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, was sentenced by a <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION> court in April to 13 years in prison for his part in kidnapping the West Germans, allegedly to win <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s freedom. The two West Germans have since been freed.
