<SECOND>PM-Oil Imports,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Imports Highest Since 1979, API Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil imports last year jumped to the highest level since 1979 as consumption rose and domestic production hit a 12-year low, an industry trade group said today. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, representing the major oil producers and refiners, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil production fell to 8.1 million barrels a day, a nearly 3 percent drop from 1987. The rate was the lowest since 1976, the year before production began at the giant <LOCATION> Prudhoe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> oil field on the North Slope of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. Oil production in the 48 contiguous states last year was the lowest since 1950, the group said. Imports of oil surged to a rate of 7.2 million barrels a day, a nearly 9 percent increase over 1987. The record peak for oil imports was 8.8 million barrels a day in 1977, two years before the Iranian revolution sparked the secon oil crisis of the decade. The rise in imports and drop in domestic production highlight what the independent, mostly smaller, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil producers say is an urgent need for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to adopt some form of legislation to protect the industry from cheap foreign oil. One proposal likely to face the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is a fee on imported oil, which proponents say would curb the trend toward higher imports and lower domestic output. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> has not taken an official position on this issue. The institute's latest report said total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> energy use last year rose to the highest level ever, to 80 quads, a standard measure of energy consumption that is equal to a quadrillion British thermal units. One Btu is defined as the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit. Despite the rise in overall energy use, oil's share of total consumption continued to decline, to 42 percent, compared with 43 percent in 1987 and 49 percent in 1977. Use of electricity, coal and natural gas all rose by about 5 percent last year, the report said. Gasoline consumption continued an upward trend last year, but at a slower rate than in recent years. Use rose 1.6 percent in 1988, which the trade organization attributed in part to a general decline in retail gasoline prices in recent years. Consumption had risen 2.4 percent in 1987 and 3 percent the year before.
</TEXT>
