<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite warnings from other <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials, former Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> remained blind to ethical problems raised by his actions on behalf of lobbyist <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. The report, issued Tuesday, concludes that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> violated federal ethics standards. An attachment to the report shows more than 600 contacts between <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> lawyer from the time the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration came to power. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s assistance to scandal-plagued <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 and 1983 and his efforts on behalf of a proposed <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> oil pipeline in 1985 were three instances in which his friendship with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> `` dictated'' federal actions, said the report by the department's Office of Professional Responsibility <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, who collected $ 1.3 million from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> from 1982 to 1986, is awaiting trial in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on racketeering and other charges. He is accused of peddling his connection to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>. White House spokesmen <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> believes that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, his longtime friend, had done nothing wrong. And he said `` this report was unnecessary, partly because Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has not been in the office for some time and partly because it was unwarranted.'' Then-Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and criminal division chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> `` recognized the impropriety of Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s activities and advised Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> to repudiate them,'' said the report, but <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> continued to meet with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> and receive letters and memos from him as he had since 1981 <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> resigned last March to protest <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s continued tenure at the department while he was under criminal investigation. `` Despite the ability of others to perceive potential problems with Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s actions, Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> remained blind to them and made no effort to distance himself from Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>,'' the ethics report concluded. It said that other people who were n't even close to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> `` could recognize problems with Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s actions'' and that `` certainly Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s internal warning bell should have gone off.'' The report is especially critical of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s actions in connection with the oil pipeline, in which <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> arranged a meeting between then-national security adviser <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s client, Swiss oilman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>. At the time, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was liable for legal fees to <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, who had represented him in a criminal investigation in 1984. `` Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> knew when he became involved in the pipeline matter that Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> had a financial interest in the project and that he was potentially liable to Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'' for more than $ 142,000 in legal fees, said the report. `` Despite this knowledge, Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> acceded to Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s request that he call Mr. <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s fees eventually were paid by the government. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> complained that the report had an `` emotional undertone'' about <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> that was designed `` to slam him personally.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> both had acted properly and called the department's report `` old news.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> simply asked <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> to ensure that <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> was being treated fairly in connection with a $ 32 million Army engine contract and that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> `` did n't participate'' in resolving a 1983 problem involving financing for the company. <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> eventually was awarded the no-bid contract. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said in regard to the more than 600 contacts between <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> that `` <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> put all this in writing. We know there's nothing wrong.'' But the <ORGANIZATION> OPR </ORGANIZATION> report said that many letters and memos contain a `` strong undercurrent'' in which <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> is `` seeking action'' from <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and his staff on matters in which <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> had a financial interest. `` Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> traded on his ability to invoke Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s authority to facilitate achieving the ends he sought,'' the report said `` Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, it appears, was, at best, oblivious to Mr. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>'s method of operation.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s successor as attorney general, <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, tried to avoid characterizing the <ORGANIZATION> OPR </ORGANIZATION> report in any way, but ultimately disagreed with one of its conclusions while saying the others were adequately based on facts. He said the report is a `` roadmap'' on how to respond to certain types of situations. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> disagreed with one conclusion that said <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> violated ethical standards when he failed to sell $ 14,000 in stock of regional telephone companies while participating in department decisions affecting them. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> decided last summer not to prosecute <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, although <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> concluded <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had probably twice violated conflict-of-interest laws in connection with his telephone holdings and had violated tax laws in connection with failing to report the stock sales. The <ORGANIZATION> OPR </ORGANIZATION> investigation involved ethical rather than criminal aspects of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s actions.
