<HEAD>Ski Resorts Ordered to Inspect Lifts After Cracks Are Discovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State officials have ordered nine ski resorts to immediately inspect ski lifts after cracks were found in a chairlift. In an emergency session Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Passenger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tramway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> gave the resorts one week to test up to 47 lifts for cracks in a metal brace on chairs. The lifts will not have to be dismantled and can be used in the meantime. Fractures were found in four chairs at <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> during routine maintenance Saturday. The lift was immediately shut down. Tramway board engineer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrick </PERSON> said the cracks resulted from metal fatigue. `` You try to decide how excited to get about something like this,'' he said. `` Faced with four broken chairs, I'm moderately excited.'' The chairs bear the trademark <PERSON> Yan </PERSON> and were designed by Lift Engineering and Manufacturing of <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. `` It's not as if the chairs were on the verge of falling off,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON>, mountain manager at <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION>. `` They were n't dangling by a thread. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON>, plant manager at <ORGANIZATION> Lift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION>, said the company is trying to find ways to reinforce the connection. `` We are asking other ski areas if they too have this problem,'' he said. `` There have been no real incidents.''
