 Jan. 16 The <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> -RRB- Tribune on insurance for bank and thrift deposits: In its final report, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION> made an interesting recommendation: lower the ceiling on federally insured deposits in banks and thrift institutions. Deposit insurance is a Depression-era idea that once made sense. It discouraged runs on banks and gave small savers a safe place for their money. Recently, however, it contributed to a national crap shoot that may cost the public $ 100 billion. In 1980, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> unwisely raised the insurance limit to $ 100,000 from $ 40,000. Thus a device designed to protect mom and pop depositors became a no-lose game for the wealthy, who could put a no-risk $ 100,000 in one bank _ or $ 1 million in 10 banks. Because of go-go banking, money brokers, lax regulation and deposit insurance, the taxpayers are about to take a huge hit to rescue the thrift industry. The way to protect themselves from a future hit is to stop guaranteeing other people's unwise investments.
