 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. SENTENCING The court ruled that a new sentencing system that took effect in November 1987 for people convicted of federal crimes is constitutional. By an 8-1 vote, the justices upheld the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Sentencing Commission's rules and the validity of the commission itself. The cases are <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-7028, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON>, 87-1904. LABOR UNIONS The court ruled that labor unions may not fire elected local union officials who disagree with policies of the parent union. The 8-0 decision permits a union business representative in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area to sue the <ORGANIZATION> Sheet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for his allegedly illegal firing. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> Webster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 87-1303. WEST VIRGINIA TAX The court unanimously struck down a tax in a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> county </LOCATION> that permitting some property to be taxed at up to 35 times more than neighboring comparable property. But the court, referring to the county tax as `` aberrational'', declined to say whether similar state taxes also are unconstitutional. The case is Sheet Metal Workers vs. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, 86-1940.
