<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-designate <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> told big-city mayors today he would be an activist and advocate for solving housing and other urban problems, calling himself `` a big-L liberal'' on urban issues. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, addressing the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, cited the problems posed by federal budget constraints but spoke enthusiastically about working with mayors, whose complaints about cuts in federal aid to cities have been a constant refrain. `` I'm going to throw the labels out. We're going to throw out ideology,'' said the former <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman chosen by President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to head the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> and urban Development. `` I am going to be an activist. I'm going to be an advocate. The door is open. My mind is open.'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, a conservative who unsuccessfully sought the Republican presidential nomination, drew applause from the mayors when he described himself as `` a bleeding heart conservative'' and `` a progressive conservative.'' He added, `` I want to be considered a big-L liberal'' on race, poverty, and relations between mayors and <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> listened as mayors described problems in their cities caused by a shortage of affordable housing and cuts in federal housing aid and other programs. He noted that he has been associated with tax reform but said `` it went too far when it comes to affordable, low - and moderate income housing. He added: `` I'm speaking for <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> now, I'm not speaking for the administration.'' The conference on Tuesday released a survey showing increased hunger and homelessness in mayor <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities, particularly among families and children. Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., the new chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, called the findings `` a devastating indictment of the neglect of the needs of our major urban centers. He said the mayors make a `` compelling case'' for more federal assistance to help the homeless problem. `` devastating indictment'' of the neglect of urban America. <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s budget proposal for fiscal 1990 virtually ignores the problem of urban homelessness and that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will expect a revised proposal from the new administration. `` Families _ women and children _ they make up the most significant increase we have experienced'' in homelessness, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said in releasing the findings. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said the rate of increase in hunger and homelessness seemed to slow from the previous year. He attributed that in part to increased emergency services provided by state and local governments. Officials in every city surveyed cited the lack of affordable housing as the main cause of homelessness. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> cited the decline in federal spending on low-income housing during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` Shelters are not the answer,'' <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said. `` Permanent, affordable housing _ that is the answer.'' Among the survey's findings were that in the last year in the 27 surveyed cities: _ Requests for emergency shelter increased an average 13 percent All but two of the cities reported an increase. The rate of increase had been 18 percent in a similar survey a year ago. _ Requests for emergency food were up in nine of 10 cities, by an average 19 percent Three-fifths of those asking for emergency food were members of families. _ An average 19 percent of the requests for emergency shelter went unmet; among homeless families, 23 percent of requests were unmet Shelters in two out of three cities reported they turn away homeless families because of a lack of resources. _ In 62 percent of the cities, emergency food assistance facilities had to turn away people because of lack of resources _ On average the composition of the homeless population was 49 percent single men, 34 percent members of families, 13 percent single women and 5 percent unaccompanied youth One in four was a child. An average 34 percent of homeless were substance abusers and one-fourth were severely mentally ill; 23 percent had full-time or part-time jobs; 26 percent were veterans. The survey was conducted in 27 cities whose mayors sit on the conference's task force on hunger and homelessness. They were: <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, P.R.; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>.; <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul <