li Finance Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> was expected to take up the matter with Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> when he begins a four-day visit to <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> today. The Merck chemical company on Tuesday notified government officials it had shipped 19 tons of a chemical solvent to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> last year, adding that the destination may have been the suspected poison gas plant in <LOCATION> Rabta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Merck </PERSON> has regular business dealings with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, most involving small deliveries of chemicals and medicines to hospitals and universities, said company spokesman <PERSON> Hans-Joachim </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON>. On the same day, <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Barmann </PERSON>, head of the local branch of the Rhenus transportation company in <LOCATION> Cologne </LOCATION>, said his firm had entered into contracts with I.B.I. in 1986, 1987 and 1988 to deliver materials to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. `` Construction materials and, in one case, chemicals were involved,'' <PERSON> Barmann </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Barmann </PERSON> declined to provide further details, adding that federal customs officials had seized the company's records as part of the Libyan probe. Other West German companies reportedly involved include the <ORGANIZATION> Salzgitter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industriebau </ORGANIZATION> company, which according to <ORGANIZATION> Stern </ORGANIZATION> magazine made the plans for the facility 60 miles south of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Salzgitter </PERSON> <PERSON> Industriebau </PERSON>, which is fully-owned by the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> government, has denied participation. Also Tuesday, the <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Teves </PERSON> company of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> to