<HEAD>The Old Reagan Gang Leaves Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> is going skiing. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> is going back to school. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is going to have to get a driver's license. As <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency comes to an end, so do the heady times atop <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s power structure for many members of his Cabinet and other ranking officials of the administration. Some are staying on with President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, including Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON>, Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, and administration veteran <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who will be the new secretary of state. But for some of the others, January has meant packing boxes, selling homes and deciding what to do next. In some cases, what's next may be a fat salary and a job with a big law firm or corporation Or it may mean taking it easy. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> have sold their house in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and booked a commercial flight back home to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on Inauguration Day. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> plans to write his memoirs and consider what else to do. He has a standing offer to return to teaching at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, but he appears to have left behind the corporate world, where he earned $ 1 million a year as an executive of <ORGANIZATION> Bechtel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. But first things first. After 6 -LCB- years of being chauffeured and accompanied by security agents, and not driving a car once, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> plans to take the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> driver's test to obtain a new license. He will keep a bodyguard for at least a month after leaving <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Housing and Urban Development Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the only member of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s original Cabinet to last all eight years, plans to return to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, where he has kept a home two blocks off Central Park. At age 66, he'll return to practicing law, although he says he may not return to the firm he left in 1981. `` I've been in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> three times,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said. `` I served under three separate presidents. And each time I always do the same thing _ I go back to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and practice law and join a bunch of boards of companies.'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>, secretary of <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION>, is going to think about what to do next while spending the remainder of the winter skiing in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. `` I'm going to have to get serious about earning a living,'' <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said. `` And I really at this point do n't have any idea.'' He's sold his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> home and has bought one west of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. He's also bought a season ski pass for four big ski areas there. `` I think I'll make a better decision about what I should do and what I should be in the future after a little of that,'' he said. <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, secretary of labor for little more than a year, will resume studies at the <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION>, where she was studying when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked her to join the Cabinet. She had worked at the treasury and interior departments earlier in the administration. Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> says he'll sleep in on the day after the inauguration _ and maybe the next day, too. `` I intend to take it easier,'' he said. `` I've reached that age -LRB- 70 -RRB- when I do n't have to worry about justifying myself every day, so I'm not going to worry about that.'' He came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> 20 years ago when <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> named him an assistant secretary of agriculture. He plans to remain, but is considering buying a second home in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Health and Human Services Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, also 70, has put his condominium on the market. He plans to retire to rural <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, where he was a doctor, and spend his time reading, writing and tending to his five acres. His first priority is getting tomato seedlings going in his greenhouse in time for spring transplanting. He's bought a riding lawnmower and recently installed a hot tub in the greenhouse, for relaxing after all that work. Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> plans to return to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and his real estate investments. He's considering job prospects, and he seems to be in a hurry to get started. He's booked on a plane out Thursday night, the evening before Inauguration Day. Commerce Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON>, 71, who has been in the job just 14 months, will return to his home in <LOCATION> Beaufort </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION> His agenda: fishing, hunting, golf, tennis and sailing. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carclucci </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> secretary, says he'd like to find a job outside government and remain in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I've given thought to it but I have n't decided anything,'' he said. `` It's a little hard from this perch to look around for jobs. Every time somebody calls me on the phone, I have to disqualify myself.'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and a close friend of the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION>, will return to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> with his wife <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>, a former band leader whose name originally was <PERSON> Zwick </PERSON>, plans to resume doing what he was doing before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s election _ arranging financing for movies and other show business deals. A son, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wick </PERSON>, produced the hit movie `` Working Girl.''
