<HEAD>Athlete Begins Cross-Country Fund-Raiser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A disabled athlete rolled away from City Hall in his wheelchair Tuesday, embarking on 5,000-mile, 20-state trek to raise money for paralysis research. `` I want people to realize that living with a disability does not limit one's ability to live life to the fullest,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON>, 26, a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> native who was paralyzed from the waist down in a car accident seven years ago. As a Dixieland band played, four motorcycle officers escorted <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> as he headed out of the city on a trip that he hopes will wind up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in July. Dozens of corporations have helped fund <PERSON> Duff </PERSON>'s Wheels Across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> journey. Project organizers hope he will inspire contributions to the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Project to Cure Paralysis, a program sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION>.
