<HEAD>Chicago Company Signs Consent Decree on Water-Filter Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> company has agreed not to contend in ads that its water treatment system removes certain chemicals unless it can back up what it says, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The company, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, signed a proposed consent decree that also requires it not to claim without substantiation that the membrane cartridge of its Pollenex Bottled Water Maker Reverse Osmosis System can last a year without replacement. The commission's complaint said the company had contended in advertising that its system removed `` up to 99 percent of organic chemicals and other contaminants from tap water,'' and nearly all or most of the family of chemicals called trihalomethanes, which can be produced by chlorination. However, the company had no basis for that claim, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said. Under the decree, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> must have a `` reasonable basis'' for any claims of performance or longevity of its water treatment products. By signing the decree, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> neither admitted nor denied guilt. However, it will make itself liable for a fine of $ 10,000 if it should be found to have violated any terms in the future, if the decree is adopted. The commission will receive public comment on the decree until March 20, after which it will decide whether to adopt it.
