<HEAD>Teddy Bear Blamed for False Alarm at School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTLEGAR, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security guards, baffled for eight days by false alarms at <ORGANIZATION> Twin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rivers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, have found the culprit: a teddy bear. Principal <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Phipps </PERSON> said the mystery was solved when a maintenance worker smacked his hand down on a ladder in frustration. The teddy bear replied with a beep. The bear, a learning tool for special needs children, responds with a beep to touch, movement or sound, <PERSON> Phipps </PERSON> said. Someone had left the bear on a heat register. Every time the hot-water heater clanked at night, the bear beeped, triggering a silent alarm repeatedly over the winter holidays. `` All we had to do was move the toy,'' <PERSON> Phipps </PERSON> said. `` The bear's been behaving himself ever since.
