<HEAD>Family Starts Campaign Urging Mondale for U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> said he'll decide sometime this year whether to run for his old <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat in 1990. <PERSON> Suzie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON>, an activist in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic-Farmer-Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said she and her family mailed 400 letters last weekend to party officers and delegates, asking them to write to <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> and encourage him to run against Republican Sen. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Boschwitz </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON> said Tuesday that she plans to mail another 400 letters. <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON> said she hoped to show <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> that he has grassroots support. She said she initiated the letter campaign without talking to <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>. `` It's flattering, of course,'' said <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, adding he would make a decision later this year. `` We may not have been capable of making him president, but we can certainly return him to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, 61, was attorney general from 1960 until appointed in 1964 to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where he remained until 1977. He was vice president from 1977 to 1981. After losing the 1984 presidential election, he returned to <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> to practice law.
