<FILEID>AP-NR-01-18-89 1254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FactoryUse     01-18 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Use,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Use Inches to Nine-Year High in December</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry operated at its highest rate in nine years last month, the government reported Wednesday, but analysts said the modest pace of growth should allay fears of increasing inflation. Use of industrial capacity at factories, mines and utilities rose 0.1 percentage point to 84.2 percent last month, the highest rate since it hit 84.3 percent in November 1979, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said. The operating rate for November 1988 was a revised 84.1 percent, and October's figure was 84.0 percent. In an accompanying report, the agency said industrial production climbed a moderate 0.3 percent in December following a revised increase of 0.4 percent in November. While high operating rates can cause concern that factories will have trouble meeting demand, resulting in shortages and higher prices, economists said December's increases were small enough that they did n't point to higher inflation. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, consultants in <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said the reports were `` consistent with continued recovery in the industrial sector and moderate growth in the economy as a whole.'' `` It's probably the best of both worlds,'' he said. `` It showed continued expansion but at a moderate pace.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said that while operating rates were high, the specter of inflation `` does n't seem to be as much on our doorstep as some people have pretended. On the other hand, <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> expressed concern that production `` is not increasing fast enough to satisfy domestic demand and to make progress'' on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, which widened to $ 12.5 billion in November. At manufacturing plants, the operating rate climbed to 84.4 percent last month from 84.3 percent in October. The operating rate for durable goods _ `` big ticket'' items expected to last at least three years _ rose by 0.1 percentage point to 83.0 percent, while the rate for non-durable goods fell by a like margin to 86.4 percent. Industries with especially strong operating rates over the past two years include primary metals, chemicals, fabricated metal products, non-electrical machinery, autos and automotive parts. Capacity utilization for manufacturers of motor vehicles and parts rose for the fifth straight month to 88.1 percent, up from 85.5 percent in November. The December operating rate at utilities was 81.9 percent, up from 81.3 percent a month earlier. In the mining, which includes oil and gas drilling, the operating rate was up 0.1 percentage point to 83.3 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s industrial production index now stands at 140.2 percent of its 1977 base, reflecting sharp gains in auto production and continued strength in production of construction supplies. The index has not declined since September 1987, reflecting an export-driven manufacturing boom accompanied by a surge in spending for capital equipment to expand and modernize factories. Production in manufacturing rose 0.3 percent in December following a revised increase at the same rate for the month earlier. Automobiles were assembled at an annual rate of 7.9 million units, up from 7.6 million in November. Production of light trucks also rose. Output at mines was unchanged in December after a 1.4 percent rise a month earlier. Production at utilities was up 0.8 percent from November. Total output at factories, mines and utilities was up 4.7 percent from a year earlier.
</TEXT>
