<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> technician pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges he tried to sell anti-submarine warfare secrets to the Soviets. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doumar </PERSON> set an April 3 trial for <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunkle </PERSON>, 39, of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, who was arrested and charged with espionage Jan. 10 in an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> sting. <PERSON> Kunkle </PERSON> said he wanted to become a Soviet spy for the money and to get back at the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, which discharged him for indecent exposure in 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. The former chief petty officer is confident he will be exonerated, and `` his spirits are good,'' defense attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said after the arraignment. `` There are two sides to every story. All you've heard so far is what the government claims occurred in this case,'' he said. <PERSON> Kunkle </PERSON>, a hospital security guard, was arrested in <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> by two <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents posing as Soviet officials. As a hidden camera recorded the meeting, <PERSON> Kunkle </PERSON> revealed secret information that he recalled from his job as an anti-submarine warfare instructor four years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Kunkle </PERSON> was paid $ 5,000 for the information, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said no classified information reached the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kunkle </PERSON> remained jailed without bail. An <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent last week testified that <PERSON> Kunkle </PERSON> called himself smarter and more professional than former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORG