<TEXT>
 Many of the high-powered Republicans who came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to see <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> become president evidently were a bit hesitant about his chances _ until the pollsters told them to relax and reserve. All 240 rooms and suites at the capital's plush Ritz-Carlton are booked, including one offered as part of a $ 15,000 inaugural package the hotel proudly boasted included `` the most expensive hotel room in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.'' But bookings were slow for a while. Hotel spokeswoman <PERSON> Vivian </PERSON> <PERSON> Deuschl </PERSON> said the pace of reservations for the inaugural appeared tied to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s lead in the pre-election polls. `` Every time <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went up in the polls we got more phone calls,'' Ms. <PERSON> Deuschl </PERSON> said. `` Then, when everybody was saying it was all over we started getting requests for room blocks.'' By Election Day, the <PERSON> Ritz </PERSON> was booked for inaugural week. The least expensive room is $ 290 a night, with a four-night minimum this week. Those lucky enough to land a suite pay between $ 800 and $ 1,200 a night. Among the <ORGANIZATION> Ritz </ORGANIZATION>'s registered guests is real estate mogul <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who apparently signed up for the four-night minimum although he plans to spend just two nights in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, arriving Thursday, attending the swearing-in ceremony Friday and one of the balls that night.
