n lest lives be necessarily be lost. <PERSON> Mendis </PERSON>' lawyer, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON>, said his client also feared Sinhalese groups fighting Tamil demands for an independent state. <PERSON> Chandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Monerawela </PERSON>, the Sri Lankan high commissioner to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, said `` <PERSON> Mendis </PERSON> is an unknown entity in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> _ he is not wanted for any criminal or civil offense.'' <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON> said he will challenge the deportation in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, although his client already has lost two immigration appeals. Last month, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s highest court, the Law Lords, refused to hear the case. The Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Methuen </PERSON>, the vicar whose church gave <PERSON> Mendis </PERSON> asylum, said police broke into his home, cut telephone and burglar alarm wires, and smashed in the door of the vestry where <PERSON> Mendis </PERSON> slept. `` There is quite a lot of damage to the building,'' he said. Church council member <PERSON> Ingrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Falat </PERSON> said police cut <PERSON> Mendis </PERSON> free and carried him away. Greater Manchester Assistant Chief Constable <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, however, described the operation as `` low-key'' and denied that police had cut telephone or alarm wires. He offered to repair the damaged doors. <LOCATION> Methuen </LOCATION> and the bishop of <PERSON> Hulme </PERSON>, the Rt. Rev. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, said the government's action will jeopardize <PERSON> Mendis </PERSON>' chances of getting asylum outside <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>.
