<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An internal audit by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says that federal control of illegally high traces of pesticides and other chemicals in the nation's meat and poultry supply has been slipshod and sometimes ineffective. The investigators found that in some cases meat and poultry containing too much of these chemical residues slipped through and got into the consumer pipeline. `` Even when animals were presented to inspectors, -LRB- agency -RRB- administrative controls and current policies did not ensure timely and effective response when pesticide residue was suspected or found in meat and poultry products,'' the report said. `` As a result, some adulterated products were allowed to enter commerce.'' The report by the department's Office of Inspector General said the department's inspection agency _ the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION> _ has little authority to prevent pesticide residues from showing up in meat and poultry. Accordingly, the <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION> has turned to the food industry itself for cooperation in monitoring levels of chemicals and ferreting out violations. The agency's chief responsibility is to ensure that USDA-inspected meat and poultry products are safe, wholesome and free of adulterating chemicals. As part of its responsibility, the agency samples and analyzes edible tissues to see if they meet the federal standards. But the system is far from foolproof, and the agency also includes efforts to enlighten farmers and processors about the federal standards and how to comply with them. The report, which was completed last November but not given wide distribution by the department, said <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION> was `` unable to successfully investigate pesticide violations in 79 percent of the cases'' reviewed by the auditors. A violation was defined as an illegal level of chemical residue found in a sample of meat or poultry. Some of the reasons for the lack of success in investigating violations included: _ Tracing the illegal residue to the original producer was not always successful _ Follow-up samples from suspected meat were seldom taken, or else the suspected animals or carcasses were not always retained for further checking _ Documentation of regulatory actions was insufficient Starting in June 1986, when a company signed a memorandum of understanding with <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION>, it agreed to upgrade its own quality control procedures, was exempted from routine monitoring by the agency and placed under a less-intensive monitoring program. `` In addition, these companies became eligible to make certain claims on their product labels concerning -LRB- chemical -RRB- residue levels or superior quality control procedures,'' the report said. By 1988, this `` verified production control'' program included 11 companies and 34 slaughter plants out of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> total of 1,800 plants. The participating plants had an annual slaughter of about 5 billion pounds, or about 8 percent of all animals slaughtered last year. In all, the agency is responsible for inspection in more than 7,000 meat and poultry slaughter and processing plants. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> investigators visited 96 federally inspected meat and poultry plants and conducted research at the agency's national office, three regional offices, three field laboratories and five USDA-accredited laboratories. One of the major problems uncovered is the identification of the original farmer, feedlot operator or other producer of livestock that have been found to be in violation of the federal residue levels. The report recommended that the agency seek legislation for mandatory identification of the source of all animal species slaughter for domestic food consumption. However, <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION> responded that such a move be directed to policy-makers, not the regulatory agency itself. <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION> administrator, said that historically the agency has pursued animal identification as a related part of the residue testing program. `` We recently were successful in obtaining a swine identification program outside of the legislative route, and would strongly support similar identification for the other species which come under our jurisdiction,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said in a response to the report.
</TEXT>
