<HEAD>New HUD Secretary Puts Fighting Poverty over Ideology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Housing Secretary-designate <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> pledged Wednesday to `` throw out ideology'' and be an advocate for helping ease poverty, homelessness and other urban problems. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> won praise from big-city mayors in his first public appearance before them since his selection by President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as secretary of Housing and Urban Development. `` I am going to be an activist,'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said. `` I'm going to be an advocate. The door is open. My mind is open.'' He spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> as the group held its annual winter meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He promised to visit many of their cities and to meet again with the organization once he is confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, a conservative who unsuccessfully sought the Republican presidential nomination, drew applause from the mayors when he described himself as `` a bleeding heart conservative'' and `` a progressive conservative.'' `` I'm going to throw the labels out. We're going to throw out ideology,'' he said. He added, `` I want to be considered a big-L liberal'' on race, poverty, and relations between mayors and his department. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> referred briefly to federal budget constraints but spoke enthusiastically about working with the mayors, whose complaints about cuts in federal aid to cities have been a constant refrain during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. He also noted his support for tax cuts that some critics blame for cutbacks in domestic spending. `` I've long been associated with the tax reform, but it went to far when it comes to affordable low - and moderate-income housing,'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said `` But I'm speaking for <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> now. I'm not speaking for the administration.'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> cited his support for urban enterprize zones, which encourage jobs and development in targeted inner cities with tax breaks and other incentives. He listened as mayors described problems in their cities caused by a shortage of affordable housing and cuts in federal housing aid and other programs. `` I want you to know from the bottom of my heart I am really excited about this, and I have a mandate from the president-elect to pursue many of the things you've mentioned,'' he said. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> was widely praised by the mayors, who have had only limited meetings with the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary throughout <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s two terms, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> was not scheduled to have a farewell meeting with the mayors during their three-day meeting. `` This is the type of enthusiasm we have waited for for a long time,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Jessie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> News </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` We have prayed for it.''
