<HEAD>Carter and Ford Say They Can't Figure Why They Got Such Bad Press</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> had the `` killer rabbit'' to contend with and <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> was perceived as prone to bumping his head on helicopter doors. But after all these years, the two former presidents say they do n't know why they got such lousy press. `` Presidents <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and I had bad relations with the press. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had good relations,'' said <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> on Wednesday. `` Why, I do n't know.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> took part in a discussion at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> on `` The Press, the Presidency and the First Hundred Days.'' They agreed that when it comes to relations with the news media, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will find <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> a hard act to follow. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was treated with kid gloves by the press, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said. And <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> thinks <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> got away with staying aloof from tough issues _ `` a tribute to his acuity.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said he had unsuccessful relationships with the press. He said he spent weeks trying to deflect attention from a story that a rabbit had swum out to his boat as he was fishing and that he had to beat it back with oars. `` How can you control something like that?'' <PERSON> Cartr </PERSON> asked. The rabbit story, he said, `` gave an image of an incompetent president who could not even protect himself against a rabbit.'' He said that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> `` was the best athlete ever in the White House'' but that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> was dogged by stories about his golf balls hitting bystanders and his clumsiness generally. `` It hurt him politically,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said news people who accompanied him on ski trips to <LOCATION> Vail </LOCATION> fell as much on the slopes as he did `` but nobody took pictures of them.'' The images are hurtful, he said, but `` it's part of what they think the public wants.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said that when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> takes the oath of office this week he will start out with the best atmosphere, since relations between the press and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in recent weeks have been pleasant.
