<HEAD>Government Again Changes Stance On Libyan Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Wednesday again changed its position on when it knew about a suspected chemical weapons plant in <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, and opposition lawmakers shouted their disapproval in Parliament. The latest switch came amid accusations by the opposition that the government tried to cover up alleged involvement by West German companies in the Libyan project. <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON>, Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s chief of staff, delivered a long address in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> defending the government's actions <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> informed West German officials May 18 about possible German involvement in the Libyan plant. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> alleges the plant was intended to produce chemical weapons. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> says it will produce pharmaceuticals. The May 15 date is five months earlier than what the government acknowledged Monday and six months earlier than the Nov. 15 date West German leaders mentioned three weeks ago. Opposition lawmakers shouted and hooted during the speech. When the scandal first broke three weeks ago, West German leaders angrily denied <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allegations German firms were involved in the plant. They also denied having any knowledge the complex may be intended for production of chemical weapons. <PERSON> Norbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gansel </PERSON>, a lawmaker with the opposition Social Democrats, spoke after <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> and criticized the government's handling of the growing scandal, which has led to criminal investigations into two West German companies. `` The question is, what you knew and what you did about it,'' <PERSON> Gansel </PERSON> said. He added, `` You, <PERSON> Herr </PERSON> <PERSON> Chancellor </PERSON>, are politically and personally responsible that the German and international public were deceived for a long time.'' Officials have said the government did not immediately say what it knew because that would have jeopardized West German investigations. <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> told lawmakers that in August 1987, the West German <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> received information the plant `` in all probability'' was intended for producing chemical weapons. He said at the time there was no evidence of West German involvement in the plant. <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> also said that `` on the basis of intelligence reports, we must assume that this plant in <LOCATION> Rabta </LOCATION> is intended to produce chemical weapons.'' On Tuesday, chief government spokesman <PERSON> Friedhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Ost </PERSON> refused to say whether <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> had evidence backing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> charges about the plant. According to <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON>, `` new reports'' by the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` gave clear indications of involvement by German companies'' in the Libyan factory. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> received his first `` comprehensive'' report on the suspicions Oct. 20, <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> also provided new information about West German investigations into the affair. He said that on Dec. 14, West German investigators met with an `` informant'' who gave them documents indicating involvement by the German firm Imhausen-Chemie in the Libyan plant. According to <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON>, the informant said other documents could be obtained from I.B.I. Engineering, a now-defunct company that was based in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. Criminal investigations have been launched against <ORGANIZATION> Imhausen </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> I.B.I. </ORGANIZATION>, which allegedly organized participation by German firms in the Libyan plant. The criminal investigations began as a result of a Jan. 4 seizure of I.B.I. documents, <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> said. He rejected any suggestion West German authorities had tried to cover up the affair. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> was present during the debate but did not speak. According to a government spokesman, <PERSON> Schaeuble </PERSON> delivered the speech because it was a matter of protocol.
