<HEAD>The Speculation Mounts: Might Bush Walk in His Own Parade?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s penchant for spontanaiety is raising speculation about whether he might just decide to hop out of his armored limousine Friday for a bit of inaugural parade handshaking. While there is no word from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> camp on whether he might decide to work the sidewalk crowds, the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is fully prepared with protection for whatever fancy might strike him, said spokesman Special Agent <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>. `` We would be derelict in our duty if we were n't prepared for that,'' he said. `` The possibility always exists ... He's the president and we're there to provide security.'' However, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said he has no information on whether <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will decide to get out of the brand new 1989 Ford <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> town car. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would n't be the first president to walk in his own parade. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> got out of his limousine in 1977 and walked hand in hand with his wife <PERSON> Rosalynn </PERSON> for much of the distance down <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Avenue. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did not follow suit in 1981, remaining inside his car. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s black limousine, which is being used for the first time, has a bit less window area than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s did, so that people will have less chance of glimpsing him inside. Both before and since his Nov. 8 election, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has set a style that is much more spontaneous than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s. He likes to dine spur-of-the-moment at local restaurants and has turned up a local clothing or specialty shops. During the campaign <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would occasionally stop his motorcade to chat with farmers in their fields or schoolchildren by the road. On one occasion a rural restaurant got word that he might stop for a meal and the proprietors became irate when he instead walked into a mom-and-pop store next door and bought a couple slices of pizza to go.
