<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ogonyok     01-18 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ogonyok,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>One of Glasnost's Vanguard Publications Attacked by Top Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A trail-blazing Soviet magazine and its editor-in-chief came under fire from the two most prominent newspapers Wednesday, with one printing a letter that denounced the weekly as `` scum'' bent on defaming Soviet history. Under President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the magazine <ORGANIZATION> Ogonyok </ORGANIZATION> and its chief, <PERSON> Vitaly </PERSON> <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON>, have become widely known and increasingly controversial. Many of the sensational revelations made by Soviet media under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` glasnost,'' or greater openness, have appeared in <LOCATION> Ogonyok </LOCATION>. In this week's issue, the slick magazine with more 3 million subscribers nationwide revealed Soviet suicide statistics for recent years, denounced pollution and ran the latest episode of an expose on corruption and cronyism under the late leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. Seven prominent cultural figures, in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily newspaper Pravda, bitterly attacked <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON>, saying it had gone `` far outside the bounds of literary arguments.'' `` The magazine has taken upon itself the role of a kind of judge on all questions of social life, politics, the economy, culture and morals,'' they wrote. The seven grouped <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON> along with Soviet publications they said are engaged in an `` unprecedented distortion of history, and that revise the social achievements of the people.'' They accused it of printing unverified hearsay and of deprecating Soviet cultural icons such as poet <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayakovsky </PERSON> and Nobel literature laureate <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Sholokhov </PERSON>, author of `` And Quiet Flows the Don.'' Those signing the letter, including conservative writers <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rasputin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vasily </PERSON> <PERSON> Belov </PERSON>, said they supported `` with all their souls'' the reform program undertaken by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, but had become alarmed by `` scum bubbling up on the crest of the mighty stream of renovation.'' <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON> has drawn tough and insulting criticism from other Soviet media before, but Pravda gave great prominence to the letter, printing it above the fold on its back page. That placement in the party's top daily could indicate high-level irritation at <LOCATION> Ogonyok </LOCATION> and its view of the Soviet past and present. Since the magazine has been one of the leaders in the drive for franker discussion of social problems and a more honest coming-to-grips with the country's past, any official attack on it would be perceived by many Soviets as a signal of glasnost's limits. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, the government's afternoon newspaper, ran its own correspondent's article that cast doubt on <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON>'s credibility and wondered aloud why <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON> was trying to run in a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> neighborhood for a seat in a new national assembly, the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, to be elected in March. The Ogonyok editor was seen by millions of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television viewers when <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> anchorman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON> visited with him in a segment of the network's 1987 documentary on Soviet life, `` Seven Days in May.'' Under glasnost, the magazine has been transformed from a staid journal to a lively and popular magazine. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> correspondent <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepovoi </PERSON> said he attended a Jan. 9 meeting of voters from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s 21st electoral district called to nominate <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON> to the new council. <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON> this week ran a story on the same meeting, and said it was broken up by vocal right-wing Russian nationalists extremists before the necessary quorum of 500 voters could assemble. <PERSON> Stepovoi </PERSON>, however, said not only members of the group known as `` Pamyat,'' or `` Memory,'' had caused the disorders, implying <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON> supporters also were involved. He said the shouting march began after organizers of the meeting announced they had failed to assemble a quorum and that <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON> would hold a `` creative meeting'' instead. <PERSON> Stepovoi </PERSON> also questioned why <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON> would want to run for the new assembly from a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> district, since some Soviet social organizations that are entitled to direct representation in the assembly have already named <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON> as a candidate. `` What's the point?'' <PERSON> Stepovoi </PERSON> asked. `` As <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON> has reported, <PERSON> Korotich </PERSON> was nominated as a candidate for people's deputy of the U.S.S.R.'' He added: `` I can personally note that he's been chosen by the magazine's collective.''
