<HEAD>Supreme Court Hears Case that Could Affect Racial Bias Claims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case that could affect on-the-job racial bias lawsuits nationwide, was urged Wednesday to throw out discrimination charges against <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> salmon canneries. Both sides in the case acknowledged that the industry _ a seasonal business that relies on migrant workers drawn from remote areas _ is hardly typical of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commerce. But the case could provide standards for handling job discrimination claims throughout the nation. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON>, a lawyer for two companies based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, said employers in the case have done more than their fair share of hiring minorities at canneries they operate in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. The companies `` should not be penalized'' under misplaced legal theories adopted by a lower court, <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arditi </PERSON>, representing Filipinos, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> natives and Asians, said the companies relegated the minority workers to the lowest-paying jobs in a `` pervasive'' discriminatory system. He said the minority workers were capable of doing the better-paying jobs. `` There's no question about the availability of skilled personnel'' among the minority groups, <PERSON> Arditi </PERSON> said. The court's ruling, expected by July, could clear up questions left unanswered by a ruling last June that said employees can use statistical evidence to prove that some subjective decisions made by their employers violate federal law. The court reinstated a suit by a black woman who charged a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> bank with discrimination. But that ruling failed to produce a majority of five votes for any particular legal theory, and some observers believe it could prove at best a mixed blessing for minority groups. In the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> case, non-whites charged discrimination by <ORGANIZATION> Wards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cove </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Packing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc. of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Castle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cooke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Astoria </LOCATION>, Ore The companies operate salmon canneries in remote areas of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> during the summer salmon run. Non-whites say that while they hold nearly half the jobs at the canneries, the jobs are racially stratified with whites dominating in the higher-paying positions such as machinists, carpenters and administrators. The companies said any racial divisions are for legitimate business-related reasons. For example, they said most higher-paying jobs require skill and prior experience that non-whites have difficulty acquiring because they are seasonal workers from remote regions of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arditi </PERSON>, challenging that claim Wednesday, said nepotism is pervasive in the canneries with whites hiring inexperienced youthful relatives for higher-paying jobs. `` You have 14-year-olds, 15-year-olds, 16-year-olds who are hired for upper-level jobs,'' <PERSON> Arditi </PERSON> said. Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> questioned whether that is proof of racial bias. He offered the example of a family-owned business that hires family members. One of the key issues in the case is the use of statistics to demonstrate bias _ or the lack of it. <PERSON> Fryer </PERSON> argued that statistics showing non-whites holding most of the lower-paying seasonal cannery worker jobs and fewer better positions do not prove discrimination. The relevant figures are those showing that the companies hire for the higher-ranking positions from a <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> labor market that is only 10 percent non-white, he said. The companies say they filled those more desirable jobs with more than 20 percent non-whites. A federal judge ruled in favor of the companies in 1983, throwing out the suit. But the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated the suit in 1987 and ordered a full trial. The companies appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overrule the appeals court. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is siding with the cannery owners. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the 9th Circuit court placed too heavy a burden on the companies to disprove the bias claims. The case is Wards Cove vs. <PERSON> Atonio </PERSON>, 87-1387.
</TEXT>
