<HEAD>One Expectant Mother In Five Uses Cocaine, BCH Study Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A continuing <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> study has found that 18 percent of expectant mothers, most from the inner city, use cocaine at least once during pregnancy. `` It's very alarming,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuckerman </PERSON> of the hospital's Division of Development Behavioral Pediatrics. `` Cocaine is not only bad during pregnancy, but being a cocaine abuser is not a great way for a child to be reared.'' The study is expected to be completed in six months and <PERSON> Zuckerman </PERSON> said Wednesday that researchers are still investigating the health consequences of the drug abuse. Dr. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, director of neo-natalogy at <ORGANIZATION> BCH </ORGANIZATION>, said cocaine abuse is a common problem. `` This is n't just something pregnant women do. It's something people do. We're seeing an epidemic number of people using cocaine. A lot of what we're seeing in babies is related to the amount of drugs on the street,'' she said. Some babies born to cocaine abusers have small heads, indicating their brains have n't grown adequately, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. Other potential side effects in infants are irritability, quivering, behavioral abnormalities and poor feeding ability. The study of 1,226 pregnant women was based on urine tests and interviews conducted between July 1984 and December 1987 at <ORGANIZATION> BCH </ORGANIZATION>, which serves a large portion of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s inner-city population. The study was funded by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION>. Other results of the <ORGANIZATION> BCH </ORGANIZATION> study included: _ 36 percent of the admitted drug users said they used cocaine less than once a month _ 16 percent used it up to three times monthly _ 25 percent said they used it once or twice a week _ 23 percent said they used it three or more times a week Last summer, a study by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Perinatal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Addiction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> found that at least 11 percent in 36 participating hospitals had used illegal drugs during pregnancy.
