<HEAD>FTC Acts Against Doctor Who Promised to Improve Odds of Pregnancy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has filed consumer fraud charges against a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> physician who told patients his treatments would increase their chances of becoming pregnant, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The complaint alleges that Dr. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Reproductive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Genetic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, told his patients his hormone-injection treatments had resulted in full-term, successful pregnancies for more than 80 percent of his patients. In fact, no more than 40 percent of those who received repeated injections of Human Chorionic Gonadotropin, or HCG, became pregnant, according to <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>. While HCG slightly enhances the odds of a woman becoming pregnant, the hormone is more commonly found simply as a chemical biproduct of pregnancy, usually showing up in urine tests, according to the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION>. In all, <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> treated `` several hundred women'' who lost from $ 400,000 to more than $ 2 million, <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> will be seeking a return of some or all fees collected from each patient <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> treated, <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> has also asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> to issue a preliminary injunction prohibiting <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> from making further such claims. Several of <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>'s patients have also filed civil suits against him. They are seeking recovery of fees; some also want unspecified damages. While the treatments caused no physical harm, a 38-year-old patient of <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>'s was told by another physician that she had greatly diminished her chances of becoming pregnant because the several years she spent using <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>'s program had taken her closer to the end of her fertility cycle, an <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> official said. <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> was not immediately available to comment. His license to practice medicine has not been suspended, <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
