<HEAD>Two More Die In Hospitals, Toll Now 119 In Sunday Train Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two people injured in a weekend train collision died in a hospital Wednesday, bringing the death toll in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>'s worst railway accident to 119, hospital officials said. Doctors said 116 people were still hospitalized for treatment of injuries suffered in the accident in central <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> on Sunday. Forty-seven of them suffered arm and leg fractures and may be crippled, doctors said. The doctors, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said several will require limb amputations. The crash occurred when a passenger train traveling about 50 mph rammed head-on into a mail train outside the village of <LOCATION> Maizdi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Khan </LOCATION>, 16 miles north of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>. At least 100 people died at the scene and 19 others have died in hospitals. Officials said at least 1,000 people were injured in the collision. The government has put the death toll at 82, but its count is generally considered too low due to bureacratic delays in counting the dead. <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> newspapers placed the toll at more than 200.
