<HEAD>Prosecutor: Convictions Needed In '85 Soccer Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prosecutor on Wednesday urged a judge to convict 15 Britons, two Belgian police officers and a former soccer official on charges stemming from a 1985 stadium riot that killed 39 soccer fans. `` The sentence should be an example,'' Prosecutor <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Erauw </PERSON> said during the third and final day of his closing argument. On trial are 26 Britons, two Belgian state police officers, the <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> mayor and deputy mayor, two <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> soccer officials and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosens </PERSON>, former secretary-general of the Belgian soccer federation. <PERSON> Erauw </PERSON> said two of the 26 British suspects should be acquitted for lack of proof and that he had `` reservations'' about eight other British cases. He also asked that one case be severed from the other British cases because the suspect is jailed in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on an unrelated matter. The judge's decision is expected in March. If convicted of involuntary manslaughter, the British suspects face up to 10 years in jail, although <PERSON> Erauw </PERSON> has called for terms of only up to four years. President Judge <PERSON> Peirre </PERSON> <PERSON> Verlynde </PERSON> still can override <PERSON> Erauw </PERSON>'s recommendations However, a defense lawyer said convictions are unlikely against the 10 suspects against whom the evidence was questioned by <PERSON> Erauw </PERSON>. `` He is effectively recommending the -LRB- complete acquittal -RRB- for those defendants against whom he says guilt has not been established to his satisfaction,'' said Sir <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Erauw </PERSON> said two Belgian state police officials and <PERSON> Roosens </PERSON> should be convicted. They face up to two years in jail. On Monday, he cited inadequate organization of the match by <PERSON> Roosens </PERSON>, who was secretary-genera