<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearPerformance     01-18 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Performance,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>MIT Study: Nuclear Plants Work Better Overseas Because Of Amity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American nuclear plants perform worse than foreign ones because of a lack of cooperation among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> utilities and hostility between them and regulators, says a <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> study. `` What the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- utilities do n't seem to have, typically, is a culture of reaching out to one another on a company-by-company basis,'' said professor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Golay </PERSON>, a nuclear engineer and one of the report's authors. The report, financed by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> and two electric companies, was to be released Thursday in the latest issue of the school magazine <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>. The study looked at plants in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from 1975 to 1984. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> it examined the nearly 200 light water reactors producing more than 300 megawatts. The average plant in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> produced energy less than 60 percent of the time, while most of the other countries at the end of the period were at 75 percent, said <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> professor <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, the project's chief author. `` One of our conjectures is that all elements concerned with nuclear power have not been able to work together to solve nuclear problems,'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Golay </PERSON> said that when <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> decided to improve the available of nuclear-generated power, `` they did it by making it a national goal. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has tried to do some of that, but so far, in terms of availability, it has failed.'' `` What is unique to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a highly antagonistic relationship between regulators and utilities,'' the report said. `` In other countries, relationships between regulators and utilities become strained at times, but all parties report that communication is open and forthright, with no group withholding information or acting secretly or vindictively. ... Nor do politicians attempt to interfere in regulatory decisions.'' <PERSON> Golay </PERSON> said much of the hostility `` is the consequence of operating in a goldfish bowl. In other countries they operate behind closed doors.'' Nuclear industry spokesman <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> agreed with the assessment of 60 percent efficiency. But in a telephone interview from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Awareness </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, he said, `` We're getting better.'' As for cooperation among utilities, after the 1979 accident at <LOCATION> Three </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, utilities set up a computer link to share information, and the industry also has established the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operators </ORGANIZATION>. He noted that in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, where nuclear power facilities are considered outstanding, the government owns the utility. `` That's a fairly simple relationship. Ours is more complex. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission is careful not to get too close to the industry. There's an arm's length -LRB- relationship -RRB-, as it should be,'' he said. But he added, `` I do n't think it's contributing to inefficency.''
</TEXT>
