<FIRST>r a AM-SaggingPlywood     01-18 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sagging Plywood,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Building Industry Troubled By Faulty Fire-Retardant Plywood Roofs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire-retardant plywood used to build roofs on thousands of multiple-family dwellings nationwide can weaken and collapse after prolonged exposure to the sun's heat, building industry officials said Wednesday. `` It really is not the type of problem where people will have to worry about their roofs caving in on them at night when they're sleeping,'' said <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON>, a civil engineer and president of <ORGANIZATION> Frost </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Christenson </PERSON> and Associates in <LOCATION> Florham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> But builders say the fire-retardant plywood weakens after five to six years and starts to sag, and could collapse under the weight of heavy snow. Fire-retardant plywood is marketed by several companies under various brand names. Each company uses a different compound to impregnate the wood to resist fire. The treated plywood has been used for roofing for more then a decade in multiple-family dwellings, to keep fire from bypassing firewalls and spreading easily across the roofs of adjacent apartments, but officials only recently realized there was a problem. The American <ORGANIZATION> Plywood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tacoma </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, said it first learned of the problem in 1986 when it began to get complaints from engineers. `` These were totally different than any other thing we'd ever heard about,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Zylkowski </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> APA </ORGANIZATION> scientist. `` We did n't know what to attribute the problem to. Inspectors found the problem was a chemical reaction in the fire retardant chemicals caused by the sun's heat, <PERSON> Zylkowski </PERSON> said. The chemical reaction produces an acid that weakens the wood over several years. A committee formed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION> will meet Sunday in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> to discuss a solution. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the national plywood group are advising builders to refrain from using fire-retardant wood until researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> laboratory in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, can determine what chemicals are causing the wood deterioration. `` Until the industry comes up with meaningful controls to control their problems, we will not recommend use of their products,'' <PERSON> Zylkowski </PERSON> said. `` If they do have a problem, we recommend strongly that they get assurance from the treatment companies that the problem will not recur.'' Meanwhile, builders suggest annual inspections of roofs. Many suppliers and chemical manufacturers are working with the forest products association to develop a testing method for the fire-retardant chemicals, said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> LeVan </PERSON>, a researcher for the group. Ms. <PERSON> LeVan </PERSON> said 6,000 specimens of plywood are being tested. `` We hope to be able to prove that if you know certain lengths of time that the wood is at elevated temperatures, we will be able to predict the life of the wood,'' she said. The next problem is who should pay for replacing faulty materials which have been used in thousands of dwellings. `` That's a $ 64,000 question,'' <PERSON> Frost </PERSON> said. `` Somewhere along the line, the courts will figure out who is responsible to fix it. There are a lot of discussions going on in the industry. I think the industry will find a solution which might require some changes.''
</TEXT>
