<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> will drop barriers to imports of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wine and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vintners have dropped their plea to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for action against the barriers, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> announced Wednesday. `` The agreement opens an important new market for American wine at an early stage in that market's development and it assures that our wine industry can compete fairly with Korean wine producers,'' said a statement by <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, who will be <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> secretary in the incoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> had appealed to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> under a law which lets him retaliate against the trade of countries that damage or threaten <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry. According to the announcement, the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government is to lift immediately its ban on wine coolers, dessert wines and fortified wines, and will double its import quota for all wine products. Beginning in 1990, it will lift restrictions on table wines, wine coolers -- mixtures of wine and fruit juice -- and fruit-flavored wines. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> added that the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government has agreed to ask the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to lower the tax rate on wine coolers to 25 percent from 40 percent. In January 1991 the ban on champagne and brandy will disappear. Early last year, the South Korean tariff on wine products stood at 100 percent of their value. The current rate of 50 percent will drop to 35 percent in July and to 30 percent in January 1990. The rate on wine coolers will drop to 25 percent. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s announcement said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products will have equal access to the South Korean distribution system and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies will have the right to set up their own networks for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> products, through Korean agents. In 1991 Americans will get the right to invest directly in importing and wholesale activities on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wines. It took three rounds of negotiations to settle the dispute. The agreement on Wednesday was contained in an exchange of letters, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s office said.
