<HEAD>Offer to Legalize Solidarity Appears Likely; Jaruzelski Wins Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix byline. LEADS throughout to UPDATE with
Jaruzelski winning vote of confidence after offering to resign. Edits to
trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader said Wednesday the way is clear to make the Solidarity trade union legal again. Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> won a vote of confidence after offering to resign in a bitter internal fight. The policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s vote of confidence kept <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, party leader and head of state, in power on the second day of a meeting in which the party debated union freedoms, the official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. The meeting led to a party resolution that paves the way for the relegalization of Solidarity, said chief party ideologist <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Orzechowski </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> and other key members of the ruling Politburo, including Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> and Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, offered to give up their party and government posts, <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. In an unusual description of the heated debate, <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> reported `` accusations that party policy was incomprehensible, faulty and often contradictory of the expectations and view of party members.'' <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said the doubts of the 230-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> were justified by the `` bad experiences'' of 1980-1981. Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first independent union movement, was formed during labor unrest in 1980, crushed with martial law in 1981 and outlawed in 1982. The 230-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> gave <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> and the other leaders a vote of confidence with only four abstentions. It was the first time the government reported such a resignation offer, suggesting growing official openness. <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> passed a position paper on political and union freedoms by a vote of 143-32, with 14 abstentions. The text was not released, but <PERSON> Orzechowski </PERSON> told state radio it was a `` great turning point.'' `` It opens the road to restoration of trade union pluralism, including Solidarity, formulating at the same time a number of conditions which have to be fulfilled so the road is not too bumpy,'' <PERSON> Orzechowski </PERSON> said. `` We do n't know the reaction of the other side yet,'' he said. Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> had insisted on a clear party statement of its willingness to recognize his union before he would enter talks with the government on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s future. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the Polish leadership's `` stated willingness to relegalize the Solidarity trade union under certain conditions is a step forward. ... Relegalization would be a major achievement on the road to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s reform and recovery. We would welcome it.'' <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> had asked the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for a green light to offer to restore the union's legal status for a two-year trial period on condition it help the government in its economic and political reforms. <PERSON> Orzechowski </PERSON> said the conditions `` stem from our experiences and from the foreseen potential effects of the developing events.'' He urged the opposition to show a `` sense of responsiblity.'' A draft of the original resolution on trade union freedoms obtained by Western news agencies said that at proposed talks with the opposition, `` the organizational forms of expanded national reconciliation should be determined.'' `` There should also be agreed conditions, means and a schedule of introducing trade union pluralism, and opening the road for creation of new trade unions, including Solidarity.'' It was not known if the language concerning Solidarity was altered during the party debate in which many Central Committee members spoke against Solidarity. Solidarity has remained active despite the ban, first as an underground organization and later increasingly tolerated by authorities. Recently, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has been treated as a member of the `` constructive opposition'' whose views are carried in the media. Officials have said they would like Solidarity's support in maintaining calm as the government introduces its potentially disruptive reforms. Officials believe an agreement with Solidarity would also help the government obtain badly needed Western credits. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> urged a conditional offer of legalization to Solidarity so long as the union agrees to act as a partner, not a `` political opponent.'' He said Solidarity would have to declare itself a part of socialism and disassociate itself from anti-communist groups, observe a strike moratorium and give up financial assistance from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, which has amounted to millions of dollars. Legalization would come only after the two-year probationary period when both sides would evaluate `` positive and negative experiences,'' <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> said. A Solidarity source in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> said privately that the conditions set by <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> initially appeared `` unacceptable.'' But <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Sliwinski </PERSON>, an independent journalist associated with Solidarity, was more optimistic. Emphasizing that he was giving his own view and not the union's, <PERSON> Sliwinski </PERSON> said, `` It seems to be a commitment to recognize Solidarity. So I would would consider it an important first step that was very difficult for them.'' <PERSON> Sliwinski </PERSON> said the most difficult condition for the union to accept would be a moratorium on striking, which <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> suggested should last two years. `` <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has said many times that he does not want to organize strikes,'' <PERSON> Sliwinski </PERSON> said. `` But without the right to strike there is no use being a union.'' True partnership with the government would be impossible under those conditions `` because all the power is on the other side,'' he said.
