<HEAD>HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, the only black in <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Cabinet, brings to <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> a long-time desire to improve health care for the poor. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> has focused his efforts as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> on training doctors, especially minorities, who are willing to establish family practices in rural and inner-city areas. The 55-year-old doctor is a personal friend of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>, who was named to the medical school's board of trustees in 1983. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s selection was nearly derailed after he was quoted in an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> newspaper as saying he supported a woman's right to seek an abortion, though he opposed federal funding for the procedure. His statement inflamed anti-abortion groups and he later said he opposed abortion in all cases except in cases of rape, incest and when the mother's life is in danger, mirroring <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s view. Since the abortion flap, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> has said little about his priorities for <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION>, the largest of all the federal departments. <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> includes Medicaid, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Social Security as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> graduated with honors both from <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1954 and <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in 1958. He has taught medicine at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. In the 1970s, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> worked to establish the <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> medical school and when it separated from <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1981, he became president. It is one of the three predominantly black medical schools in the country. _ By <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ENERGY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The top issue on <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' agenda as energy secretary-designate _ repairing and cleaning up the nation's nuclear defense plants _ is one for which his military background gives him special preparation. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, 61, studied nuclear reactor engineering in 1958 at the <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, National Laboratory. He taught at naval nuclear training centers in 1960, and four years later took command of the nuclear-power attack submarine Snook. The Oak Ridge lab is one link in the Energy Department's nationwide network of nuclear weapons plants The system has been crippled recently by safety and technical problems that forced the shutdown of the only reactors that make tritium, a radioactive gas vital to the production of nuclear warheads. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> capped a 41-year <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> career with a four-year stint as chief of naval operations, the service's top job. He retired in 1986. In October 1987, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> took over as chairman of the presidential commission on AIDS that recommended legislation to prohibit discrimination against victims of the deadly disease. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> graduated from the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, in 1949, earned a master's degree at the Naval postgraduate school and then decided to specialize in nuclear submarines. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> was a protege of the late Adm. <PERSON> Hyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rickover </PERSON>, the father of the modern nuclear <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. He became commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, and in March 1982 was named chief of naval operations by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DRUG CZAR</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Early in <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s tenure as secretary of education, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> asked him what he would do if he had a magic wand to wave over American schools. `` No drugs _ none, zero, out, gone, disappear,'' replied the blunt-spoken educator. As <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice to be the nation's first drug czar, it will fall to <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> to find a way to win the war on drugs. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, 45, was a headline-grabbing education secretary who railed against rising college costs and slipshod standards. He also spoke out on topics from defense of Western civilization courses to AIDS. He left <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Cabinet in September to write, open a small policy shop called the <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, and deliver lectures at reported fees of up to $ 15,000-per-appearance. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> obtained a Ph. D in philosophy from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> and a law degree from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> He taught at several campuses and eventually ran the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> _ By <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. TRADE REPRESENTATIVE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> won swift praise when she was named as the nation's top trade negotiator But there also was grumbling. `` I had hoped that we'd have someone from the business world who had extensive international experience,'' Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said after the 54-year-old <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer was named <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative. But <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>' fans say she is fully up to whatever comes her way. Sen. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., calls her `` a tough negotiator'' and <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, the outgoing trade representative, praised her `` strong international background. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> has been underestimated before. Her 1975 nomination by President <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> as secretary of housing and urban development quickly came under fire. Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., groused that experience is too seldom valued in the nation's capital, chortling that the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Redskins </ORGANIZATION> had once lost 16 yards on a play devised by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> `` I can promise you that I wo n't be sending in any football plays,'' <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> shot back. She went on to win wide plaudits in the post. She graduated with honors from <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION>, where she captained the tennis team, and was 20th in her class of 167 at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. She served as an assistant attorney general for a year in the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> administration and has practiced law in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, where she co-founded her own law firm. _ By <PERSON> Mike </PERSON>
