<NOTE>COMMERCE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> Sr. takes over the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> without any government experience but pledging to keep communication between <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and the business community `` open and continuing and even building.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> turned to a longtime friend and stalwart GOP fund-raiser in selecting <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> to round out his economic team, saying the 61-year-old businessman would `` bring his tremendous energies to the task of promoting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports abroad.'' <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> has raised money for the president-elect in every campaign since <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ran unsuccessfully for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1970. <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>, whose fortune in oil, real estate and ranching is estimated at more than $ 200 million, founded <ORGANIZATION> Mosbacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and is an avid sailor in his off-hours. He amassed his fortune after leaving his home in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, in 1948 at age 21 to make his way in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. He first met <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who also ventured out from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> as a young man, in the late 1950s. <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON>'s primary responsibilities at Commerce will include work on opening foreign markets to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods, administering the new U.S.-Canada free trade agreement and presiding over the 1990 national census. <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> received a bachelor's degree in economics from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZA