<TEXT>
 During his 11 years in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> has been called upon to cleanse the reputations of two tarnished but vital federal agencies, first the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and since 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>. After <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won the election last November, critics of <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> pressed for his ouster as director of <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who was cast out as <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director by newly elected President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in 1977, announced on Dec. 7 that he had `` total confidence in Webster'' and that his tenure at the spy agency was `` open-ended.'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, 64, was appointed <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director in the wake of revelations that the late <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> had subverted agency operations to run his own `` off-the-shelf'' intelligence network, consisting in large part of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> operatives but working outside the oversight of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, who was born in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and trained as an attorney, still prefers the title `` judge,'' which he earned on the <ORGANIZATION> Eight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. He was summoned to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1978 by President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> to take over the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. At the time, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> was still tainted from the 48-year directorship of <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>, who threatened politicians with secret file