<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Seven Women Carry On Fight Against American Linen Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP2 of Jan. 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIBBING, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was 15 months ago when seven <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> workers walked off the job, a strike that the plant's other 35 union members did n't honor. The strikers, all women, were replaced on the strike's first day and they have long since been cut from unemployment compensation rolls. They have n't given up. Their stubborness has become a saga in this northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> town and a nationwide symbol of labor-management confrontation in an era when job security has become a prevailing issue. `` We eat, drink, and sleep the strike,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Judnitsch </PERSON>, 48. `` You just ca n't help it.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Pender </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Range </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, said the women's persistence has astonished observers. `` It was amazing that they were standing out there last winter when it was 30 below,'' <PERSON> Pender </PERSON> said. `` Well, here it is this winter and they're still there.'' Known as the <ORGANIZATION> Hibbing </ORGANIZATION> 7, they take turns picketing outside the green and white plant where they used to wash, mend and press linen for $ 5.42 an hour. They walked off the job Oct. 2, 1987, after 11 of 17 members of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> Local 1116 voted to strike rather than accept management's final contract offer. They had been working without a contract for 11 months. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, 43, said the four other workers who voted to strike immediately capitulated when it became apparent they faced dismissal. The strikers objected to a contract provision that eliminated company contributions to the union pension fund, <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> said. Instead, the company offered to put money into individual retirement accounts for workers, she said. The women also said they believe <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Pajunen </PERSON>, company president, was out to destroy the union. They cite a letter found by strikers in the company's trash. The letter, from lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON> of <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, previewed a meeting at which district executives would be briefed on `` negotiations in the <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hibbing </LOCATION> district which led to non-union status at various locations.'' <PERSON> Pajunen </PERSON> said the letter does not reflect an anti-union bias. He says the plant has operated more smoothly without a union, but adds he did not intend to break it. `` I'm not anti-labor, but they do a lot of intimidating,'' <PERSON> Pajunen </PERSON> said of unions. `` Some of the things they stand for are n't necessarily always right. <PERSON> Pender </PERSON> said the strikers would have lost interest if it were n't for favorable rulings by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s regional office in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and a federal administrative law judge in Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Leiner </PERSON> in September upheld allegations of wrongdoing made by the <ORGANIZATION> NRLB </ORGANIZATION>'s regional office. He ordered <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linen </ORGANIZATION> to reinstate the seven workers with back pay and full seniority rights. A company appeal is pending. By firing <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Judnitsch </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzick </PERSON>, 61, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, 52, <PERSON> Roberta </PERSON> <PERSON> Hecimovich </PERSON>, 46; <PERSON> Marge </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, 51, and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, 33, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linen </ORGANIZATION> unlawfully discriminated against employees engaged in a lawful union activity, <PERSON> Leiner </PERSON> wrote. The judge also said American Linen must recognize Local 1116 as bargaining agent for the <LOCATION> Hibbing </LOCATION> workers. A petition to decertify the union signed by a majority of plant workers four days after the strike began should be dismissed because the company illegally helped prepare and file it, the judge ruled. `` We've won. We're right,'' <PERSON> Judnitsch </PERSON> said. `` If we did n't feel that we were right we would n't be out there.'' <PERSON> Pajunen </PERSON> said he never fired the strikers. `` They walked off their jobs,'' he said. `` At this point not one has asked to come back.'' The company president said he would consider rehiring the strikers if any of the 70 positions open. Meanwhile, he said, he would fight any ruling from the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> that is `` untrue.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Watters </PERSON>, an attorney for Local 1116, said appeals could prolong the fight another year or two. He said the women are willing to battle until they win, bolstered by strong financial support from the union. `` Fortunately it's not too many situations that end up like this,'' <PERSON> Watters </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said she and her husband have been limited to her weekly $ 40 strike benefits and his monthly wage of about $ 700 since the strike began. `` You go from burning fuel oil to burning wood,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who has been living without any health insurance coverage since losing her job. `` You just cut corners. Sometimes it's just enough heat to keep the pipes from freezing.'' <PERSON> Pajunen </PERSON> said the strikers are `` misguided.'' `` There's probably one or two people in that group who get their kicks from doing something like this and the other people got trapped,'' he said. Not all the strikers knew each other before the walkout and now they frequently socialize after handling picket duty. `` I think we have our down days,'' <PERSON> Judnitsch </PERSON> said. `` But we're pretty hearty We're determined.'' The inevitable lows have been offset by a few highs, <PERSON> Suzick </PERSON> said. For instance, <PERSON> Crystal </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, whose successful union struggle against a southern textile manufacturer was depicted in the movie `` <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Rae </PERSON>,'' appeared at a June 25th rally on their behalf. The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> invited them on stage during a campaign appearance. In addition, the strikers say they've scored partial success in promoting a regional boycott of American Linen's service. A local school district, for example, has stopped taking the service, <PERSON> Judnitsch </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pajunen </PERSON> said the boycott has not reduced business. `` We have a plant full of happy employees producing for our customers,'' he said. `` We're not hurting.''
</TEXT>
