<HEAD>Oil, Gasoline Prices Add to Recent Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The oil markets have maintained upward momentum, fueled by buying amid speculation about possibly tighter supplies in the future. In recent days, crude oil futures prices have soared to a 14-month high. The February contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, settled Tuesday at $ 18.95 a barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, up 7 cents a barrel on the day. The last time the contract for the nearby month settled higher was Nov. 5, 1987 when the price at the end of the trading day reached $ 18.98 a barrel. At that time, there were concerns that the Iran-Iraq war could seriously disrupt shipments of crude from the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. The price of the near-month contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> now stands sharply higher than last autumn. On Oct. 5, the nearby contract sank to an intraday low of $ 12.28 a barrel. Analysts say the markets lately have derived support from a series of factors deemed promising for the price outlook, particularly speculation that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations would be able to curb their crude oil production. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said market operators are not necessarily confident that an output accord will come out of a meeting beginning Jan. 26 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> between members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> and non-OPEC countries. But, they do not expect the meeting to produce any negative news for the oil markets either, he said. The nearby West Texas Intermediate contract reached a high of $ 19.21 during the session before traders began to sell to collect profits amassed during the recent advance. Gasoline contracts in the more distant months benefited from buying partly based on thinking that new environmental specifications due to take effect this year could restrict availability in the future. Buying in gasoline spilled over into the crude oil contracts, brokers said. The February contract for unleaded gasoline rose 0.19 cent to settle at 51.10 cents a gallon. Among other refined products traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the February contract for No. 2 heating oil slipped 0.11 cent to 53.05 cents a gallon.
