<HEAD>Gulf &amp; Western Unit Tentatively Agrees to Buy Stake in TV Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the entertainment, publishing and financial services giant, plans to buy a stake in a company that owns television stations in several major markets. <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western said Tuesday its <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> had agreed in principle to a deal that would give it an option to buy a majority interest in <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns nine independent television stations. It would buy the stake from an affiliate of <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the securities firm that helped <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> finance its purchase of five television stations in April 1987. No price was disclosed for the latest deal, and it is subject to reaching a definitive agreement as well as regulatory approval. But analysts said it apparently would give <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western a relatively inexpensive entry into broadcast television. In trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western fell 62 -LCB- cents a share to $ 41. TVX jumped $ 1.62 -LCB- a share to $ 3.87 -LCB- in national over-the-counter trading. Paramount currently produces and distributes television programming. Its parent has said it wanted to become involved in TV station ownership but that high prices discouraged it. <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western would join a growing list of companies involved in TV programming that have bought television stations. Such companies feel that by getting involved in `` the retail end of distribution,'' they can exert more control over where and when their programs are aired, said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, media analyst for the securities firm <ORGANIZATION> Mabon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nugent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western said <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> had agreed in principle to acquire the right to buy <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON>'s majority investment in <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON> wound up with preferred and common stock representing a 79 percent equity interest in <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> following the television company's As the first step in the deal, <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON> would put all of its TVX common stock and enough of its TVX preferred in a new joint venture that would represent about 51 percent of <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION>'s voting common shares. Paramount would buy a 49 percent interest in the joint venture, and get an option to buy <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON>'s stake in the venture and the rest of <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> preferred stock. The statement did not say how much <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> would pay for its initial stake in the venture, but one source familiar with the deal and speaking on condition that he not be identified said it was about $ 10 million. The source said the total cost to <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>, should it acquire all of <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON>'s stake, would be between $ 125 million and $ 180 million, depending on the company's future performance. <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON> became involved with TVX Broadcast when it provided temporary financing for the concern to acquire five television stations in April 1987. Before TVX Broadcast could line up permanent financing, the stock market crashed in October 1987 and drove up potential costs of borrowing. As part of a recapitalization plan approved last November by <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> shareholders, <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> issued preferred and common stock to <LOCATION> Salomon </LOCATION>. TVX owns nine independent television stations but agreed as part of the recapitalization plan to sell four of them _ <ORGANIZATION> WTVZ </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; KRRT in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> WNOL </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>; and WMKW in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>. That will leave the company with five stations _ <ORGANIZATION> WTXF </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> WDCA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> KTXH </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> KTXA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> WLFL </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> N.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> TVX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 21.8 million on revenue of $ 138 million in the nine months ended Sept. 30, 1988, compared with a loss of $ 30 million on revenue of $ 101.7 million during the same period in 1987.
