<HEAD>Icahn Raises Stake In Texaco; Readies For Proxy Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investor <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has accused <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> management of deceiving shareholders by formulating a new anti-takeover defense after promising that an existing strategy would be allowed to expire. In a filing with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> also disclosed that he has raised his stake in the oil giant to 16.6 percent, and that he is considering another proxy challenge for control of the company. `` You know full well that a changed -LRB- ` poison -RRB- pill' would have a chilling effect on my ability _ or anyone else's _ ability to make an offer to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> shareholders,'' <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON>. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said a new effort by management to block bids for the company would in effect deprive shareholders ot `` what could be a premium of billions of dollars for their shares.'' Last June, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> lost a bitter struggle against management for control of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s board. Prior to that, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s board had rejected <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s friendly $ 60-a-share offer to buy the company. Tuesday's <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filing came in response to an article in the Wall Street Journal. The newspaper reported <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> was preparing to replace its expiring poison-pill takeover defense with a new plan. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> had assured shareholders during its proxy battle against <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> that it would eliminate the poison pill, which is aimed at making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive. Analysts have said that promise was largely responsible for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s victory in the proxy fight. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> then promised the committee representing its shareholders in the company's then-ongoing Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization that it would not issue another poison pill without the approval of shareholders or authorization from an investment banking firm designated by the committee. In composite trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock rose 50 cents to close at $ 53.50 a share. The newspaper also reported that the shareholders committee had designated the investment banker <ORGANIZATION> Rothschild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to issue a new defense and that <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeCrane </PERSON> had visited <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON>'s offices about a successor to the poison pill. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Dea </PERSON>, counsel for the equity committee, denied the panel had made any such designation. <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON> issued a statement late Tuesday saying, `` This is another case of <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> protesting without knowing what is being proposed and making claims solely for his own benefit.'' <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> is considering an interim plan to take effect when the existing pill expires in April. That plan would be in effect until shareholders have the opportunity to vote on it at <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting in May. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> officials said the plan would not preclude any legitimate offers for the company but `` would avoid anyone's acquiring control of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> through creeping purchases, to the detriment of other <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> shareholders.'' <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s biggest shareholder, said in a filing with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that he boosted his stake in <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> to 16.6 percent from 16.2 percent. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> declined to specify his intentions or to say whether a second proxy fight was likely. However, in the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filing <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said he and other investors were considering forming a slate of nominees to the four <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> board seats up for election at the annual meeting. Whether he launches a proxy battle depends on the `` nature of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s recent restructuring,'' <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> emerged from bankruptcy last April and is undergoing a major restructuring to raise $ 5 billion in cash, mainly through asset sales. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> promised to distribute $ 1.7 billion in proceeds to shareholders probably through a stock buyback early this year. In his letter to <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON>, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> alluded to the possibility of making another fight for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> if the company fails to `` sufficiently benefit shareholders in a restructuring that takes into account the higher proceeds now expected to be received from the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s sale of its 78 percent stake in the profitable Canadian subsidiary is one of the final steps in the restructuring it undertook to emerge from Chapter 11. Company observers were divided over <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s latest gestures. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Aydin </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> deserves better treatment because he is largely responsible for the rise in <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock from $ 45 a year ago. Other analysts said they were skeptical about <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s intentions since <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> could benefit handsomely if he decides to sell his shares back to <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is in his best interests to pressure <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> so they could offer him the sweetest deal possible,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuklinski </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Cowen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` He has the opportunity to get out of his stock if <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> chooses to accommodate him in some fashion and he is reminding them that might be in their best interest to do so,'' he said.
