<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Hit Record High Again, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s leading index hit another record high today, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar gained against the Japanese yen for the third consecutive day. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which fell 70.86 points on Tuesday, climbed 127.03 points, or 0.41 percent, in today's trading, closing at 31,354.55. The previous record of 31,298.38 was set last Friday. Although early trading was directionless, news reports about the possibility of a redenomination of the yen boosted buying orders, dealers said. Such a change could mean, for example, that 100 yen now would become one yen, requiring a reprinting of Japanese money. `` Participants were targeting their buying orders to redenomination-related issues such as paper, pulp and ink,'' said an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. The buying interest helped boost volume on the first section to an estimated 1.2 billion shares. The news reports quoted <PERSON> Shintaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Abe </PERSON>, general secretary of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, as saying Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was considering a redenomination of the yen. Other dealers said the majority of institutional investors stayed on the sidelines to await the announcement of monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures, expected later today in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. On the currency market, the dollar closed at 127.90 yen, up 0.20 yen from Tuesday's 127.70-yen close. The currency also opened today at 127.70 yen and ranged between 127.63 yen and 128.00 yen. The dollar now has gained 1.78 yen in three days. Trading was thin ahead of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figure announcement, a dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said. The market was expecting a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit of $ 11 billion, said the dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` If the deficit increases, it wo n't be a strong dollar-selling force because nobody expected the figure to improve dramatically in the first place,'' he added.
