<HEAD>Trade Surplus Narrows in 1988, But Was Widening in Recent Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus shrank in 1988, but was widening in the year's last four months and hit a monthly record in December, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported today. For all of 1988, the ministry said, the surplus on a customs clearance basis amounted to $ 77.4 billion, down from $ 79.7 billion in 1987. With the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 1988 surplus was $ 47.6 billion, down from $ 52.1 billion in 1987. The December surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was $ 5.03 billion, up from $ 4.92 billion in the previous December. The overall surplus in December hit a record $ 9.65 billion, up from $ 8.61 billion in the previous December and from $ 6.56 billion in November 1988. It was the fourth consecutive month when <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surplus exceeded that of the corresponding month in 1987. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s major trading partners have been pressing it for years to take greater steps toward reducing its huge trade surpluses. `` We hear the voices of concern, and we have concern,'' <PERSON> Mitoji </PERSON> <PERSON> Yabunaka </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Second </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION>, said at a news conference. `` But at the same time, we see encouraging trends.'' In December exports grew 11.6 percent from a year earlier to $ 26.1 billion, while imports grew 11.3 percent to $ 16.4 billion. Lower prices for crude oil, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s most important import commodity, coupled with strong demand overseas for Japanese-made computers, semiconductors and automobiles contributed to the record December figure.
