<HEAD>Steinburg Give $25 Million To Penn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Reliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has pledged $ 25 million to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hackney </PERSON> said today. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s gift to his alma mater is the largest single contribution in the <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>'s history, <PERSON> Hackney </PERSON> said. The money will be shared by the <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, which will get $ 15 million, and the school of arts and sciences, which will receive $ 10 million. Administrators of arts and sciences, in consultation with <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, have decided to invest the entire $ 10 million in <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION>'s English Department for faculty and student recruitment <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Overseers </ORGANIZATION> and has been instrumental in supporting the strategic plan developed by the school. As part of that plan, the school will endow five school-wide professorships, create 20 `` term chairs'' for use in a program to recruit young professors, establish a financial aid program for masters of business degrees, provide additional funding for the <ORGANIZATION> Steinberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and increase funding for new academic programs. `` All of us at <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> are deeply grateful to <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> for this act of leadership,'' <PERSON> Hackney </PERSON> said. `` He has been a champion of the university for many years, and his latest bold step is pivotal in our campaign to strengthen <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION>'s position in the front rank of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s universities.'' The money to the English department will be used to endow four professorships, create an annual visiting professorship for a nationally renowned writer, fund eight fellowships for graduate students and establish a humanities fund that will extend the department's connections with other departments of the university. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> received his bachelor's degree in economics from <LOCATION> Wharton </LOCATION> in 1959.
