<HEAD>Texas Eastern `Poison Pills' Spawn Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stockholders filed a lawsuit seeking to strike down anti-takeover measures they claim could block a $ 2.6 billion offer from <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The suit filed in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> federal court Tuesday said the measures include protections designed to drastically increase the cost of buying <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and golden parachutes that would give lump-sum severance payments to some executives fired after a takeover. The suit, filed by <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Rand </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurlander </PERSON> both of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> state </LOCATION>, contends that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and three directors might use such anti-takeover measures to entrench the directors' positions and to prevent shareholders from considering tender offers The suit claims that Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and the directors could defeat Coastal's offer unless they are blocked from using `` obstructionist'' strategies. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wichlep </PERSON> said company officials could not comment because they had not seen the suit. Named in the suit were <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and directors <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bufkin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bufkin </PERSON> is chairman of the board, King is vice chairman and <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON> is <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief executive officer The two stockholders say in their suit that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> took anti-takeover measures by adopting a poison pill plan. The plan, which comes into play 10 days after a takeover bid, entitles <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> shareholders to buy shares of the acquiring company at half the market cost of those shares. Golden parachutes for some executives also were put into place to thwart a takeover, the suit alleges. Golden parachutes are employment agreements that provide a company's key executives with lucrative severance benefits in the event that control of the firm changes hands and management shifts subsequently occur. The parachutes go into effect after an outsider acquires 45 percent or more of the stock or controls a majority of directors on the board. The parachutes are triggered if a new owner fires any of the top nine executives in the company, including <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON>, any time up to three years after the takeover. The parachutes require the owner to pay the fired executive a lump sum in cash equal to four times his annual wages, including salary and bonuses; all retirement and pension benefits that the executive would have received if he had continued to work four years more; and insurance benefits for four more years. Coastal announced Monday that it would make a cash tender offer of $ 42 per share for all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> common stock on Tuesday. The offer expires Feb. 13, unless it is extended. If the buyout is successful, Houston-based Coastal would become the nation's largest natural gas pipeline company. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> stock was the most active on the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday. It closed up 1 -RRB- at 46, after rising 14 -RCB- on Monday. Coastal stock closed at 34 Tuesday, down an eighth. Coastal holds 2.4 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s 53.1 million shares outstanding. The block of shares makes Coastal one of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest shareholders. Coastal also filed suit Monday asking that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> be prevented from filing any legal action arising from the tender offer in any court other than that of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> scheduled a Feb. 7 hearing on Coastal's suit, which includes challenges to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s poison pill protections and to anti-takeover statues in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. A lawyer for the two stockholders indicated that the investors will ask <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> to consolidate their suit with Coastal's action.
</TEXT>
