<HEAD>Camaro Continues Lock on No. 1 Stolen Car Spot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Chevrolet Camaro is continuing its lock on the No. 1 spot on a vehicle valuation services's list of most-stolen cars. Certified <ORGANIZATION> Collateral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, which sets values of stolen vehicles for insurance companies, said today the 1986 Camaro was the most-stolen car in 1988. It was followed by the 1987 Camaro, the 1984 Camaro, the 1985 Camaro and the 1981 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme. The company began compiling lists of the most frequently reported stolen domestic and imported cars in 1985, and every year since then a Camaro has topped the domestic list, <ORGANIZATION> CCC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Figel </PERSON> said. Among imported cars, the 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Excel </ORGANIZATION> topped the 1988 CCC list. It was followed by the 1985 Mazda RX7 GT and Toyota Corollas from 1983, 1982 and 1981. For its 1988 list, <ORGANIZATION> CCC </ORGANIZATION> compiled 111,440 insurance claims for stolen cars. The company defined a stolen car as one in which the entire vehicle was taken, and did not include break-ins or wheel thefts, for example. The 1986 Camaro amounted to 0.9 percent of the theft claims handled by CCC.
