<HEAD>17 Percent Of Biggest U.S. Firms Were Wooed By Foreigners In 1988:
Survey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign firms approached 17 percent of the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies about possible takeovers last year, according to a study released today by <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. Only a handful of such initial approaches by overseas firms became public or amounted to a bid, the survey found. The study _ a survey of the chief executive officers of 95 corporations with annual sales of at least $ 1 billion _ also found that while 60 percent of the respondents felt foreign ownership tends to maximize shareholder value, just over half said they would prefer a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firm as a new owner if they were taken over. Slightly less than 23 percent of the CEOs reported being approached by a prospective domestic buyer last year. Two-thirds of the chief executives responding to the survey said they were more interested in joint ventures and similar linkups with foreign companies than they were in selling. Northwestern University Professor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Zajac </PERSON>, project director for the survey, said he was surprised by the number of firms that reported overtures by foreign companies. <PERSON> Zajac </PERSON> said the survey showed `` the world is getting smaller'' and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms are finding that to survive in an increasingly complex world, they must turn to international alliances.
