<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 21-22 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Codfish ``Curio'' Leads Portuguese Quality Wine Assault</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AZEITAO, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Would you believe a wine called `` Codfish Manor?'' You should when it's a fine Portuguese red, grown by Americans on their 15th century manor, then marketed by a hard-hitting Australian intent on changing <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s image as the purveyor of cheap and unrefined wine. Quinta de Bacalhoa _ old <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Codfish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manor </LOCATION> _ is a <ORGANIZATION> Cabernet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sauvignon </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Bordeaux </LOCATION> vines planted in 1974 by <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Scoville </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> on their 30 acre renaissance-style farm or `` quinta'' in the village of <LOCATION> Azeitao </LOCATION> 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION>. The Scovilles inherited Bacalhoa from <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> grandmother <PERSON> Orlena </PERSON> <PERSON> Scoville </PERSON>, who bought it tumbledown in the 1930s and restored it to a grandeur once known under the original constructor, the mother of King Manuel I. Since the first harvest in 1979, <PERSON> Bacalhoa </PERSON> red has become one of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s better-known `` curio'' vintages that are beginning to rival the worldwide fame of historical exports like port and <LOCATION> madeira </LOCATION>. `` In <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, single quinta wines like this are sold as high-quality, connoisseur wines, in other European countries as a quality value-for-money wine and in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as a bit of a ` curio' wine,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bright </PERSON>, an energetic Australian enologist who produces and markets Bacalhoa at <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Pires </PERSON> wineries in <LOCATION> Pinhal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Novo </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Azeitao </LOCATION>. Bright arrived from <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> in 1980 and revolutionized the company's antiquated winemaking processes _ developing brand names and mass-producing wines for other exporters. Ninety percent of the company's mass-produced wine goes under contract to rival winery <ORGANIZATION> Fonseca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> for their famous Lancers brand. But Bright sticks to more traditional methods for finishing <PERSON> Bacalhoa </PERSON>. The wine is fermented without stems, painstakingly clarified with egg whites and aged for five years in <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> oak barrels, toasted on the inside to give the wine, Bright says, a different taste from regular Cabernets. It seems tradition pays off. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> called <LOCATION> Bacalhoa </LOCATION> `` <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s award-winning answer to claret,'' when it won that paper's 1984 Wine of the Year award. According to the monthly wine magazine Decanter, <PERSON> Bacalhoa </PERSON>'s `` provenance will fool most party guests. More than half the annual 8,000-case production goes abroad, with one-fourth of the exports secured by the British grocer-chain <ORGANIZATION> Sainsbury </ORGANIZATION> _ the Scovilles' first buyer in 1979. With all of <LOCATION> Bacalhoa </LOCATION> already devoted to vines, and only two small nearby areas having suitable red limestone soil, expansion is impossible. But many <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> vintners agree that single-quinta wines should not be produced en masse, but rather be the `` flagship'' of the country's wine industry. These wines constitute only a fraction of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s table wine exports, but the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> hopes their high quality will change foreign connoisseurs' perceptions that wine from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> can only be port or a famous rose. `` <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> has great potential to produce wines of similar quality to the minor French classics,'' Bright says. The <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> says <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> table wine exports fetched $ 3 billion in 1987, up from $ 2.6 billion a year earlier. Exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> increased by 11 percent to 2.2 million gallons in 1987 from 1986, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market share of rival wine exporters in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> fell. But if quality is the theme of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s push to become a fine wine exporter, wine buffs <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Metcalfe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> McWhirter </PERSON> are cautious. In their book `` The Wines of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>,'' they see only a limited prospect for quality control. Part of the reason is the temptation among some vintners to sacrifice good standards for more sales. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON>, a vintner of the northern winery <ORGANIZATION> Borges </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Irmao, also has expressed concern about the outlook for the industry because competitors are sharply discounting. He said quinta wines `` are the crowning achievement of Portuguese winemaking, but worrying signs have begun to appear that some exporters, greedy for market share, are offering wines at 30 percent below market price.'' He said there is concern that the Portuguese may fall into the same trap that hurt German winemakers, who lost a substantial part of their 40 percent share of the British market when standards fell following a price-cutting war among exporters.
