<HEAD>For Release Friday Jan. 20 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sears' Savior Rises To A New Challenge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX3 of Jan. 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cold late-afternoon rain whipped the dark surfaces of the looming Sears Tower while, inside, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> rose to make a crucial sales pitch to a roomful of skeptical stock analysts. The chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had to be tired. He'd spent nearly two hours that morning outlining a major shift in <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' retailing strategy to securities analysts in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Here he was back in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, doing it again. If <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> was beat, he did n't show it. Looking poised and confident in a dark gray suit and red tie, he stood at the podium for 1 -LCB- hours and painted a bright, if blurry, picture of the new <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> store. A `` store of superstores.'' A cluster of `` power centers.'' A lean competitor fit for battle with K mart, <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> and the electronics specialty chains. He said <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' planned switch to `` everyday low pricing,'' a strategy unveiled a week earlier, on Halloween, was `` designed to energize our company and move us forward from a position of leadership.'' The proposed sale of the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said, signaled the company's commitment to `` a low-cost mentality.'' When it was over, many of the analysts remained unconvinced that <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> was on the right track _ the one that would reverse a 4-year slide in its retailing market share and signal a return to steady profit growth. Some were disappointed that <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> had not offered a more detailed description of the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> store he sees emerging. One thing was clear: <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' 54-year-old chairman had taken hold with both hands of the latest and perhaps the most crucial challenge facing the nation's largest retailer. History has shown that when <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> tackles a <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> retailing problem, he ususally solves it. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> has been called a retailing genius, and leading 103-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> into its second century has been called his destiny. His 29-year climb from men's furnishings at a <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> store in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, to the chairman's office on the 68th floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> _ a rapid ascent by big-business standards _ is the stuff of corporate legends. The fact that he began his working life as a scrappy Irish kid from a broken home on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s West Side makes his a classic, up-by-his-bootstraps American success story as well. But it is <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>'s ties to <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' past _ his grandfather, father, mother and two uncles labored for the company _ and his triumphant turnaround of its fortunes in the early 1980s as head of the merchandise group, that already have reserved for him a place in the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> pantheon of heroes and saviors. Such an honor is not easily won. `` Sears is his life,'' said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, retired head of public affairs for <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> who now lives in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> `` More than anyone I know, he's been completely involved in <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>. He pretty much lives his work.'' Others have speculated that <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' chairman since October 1985, will work to death. But in a recent interview in a <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> conference room overlooking <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s sprawling <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, he was relaxed and congenial. `` The Lord has blessed me with pretty good energy and we usually go at it pretty strong,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said with a grin that cracked an eye-level crease across his broad face. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>'s amiable air cooled when asked whether <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> _ the originator of mail-order sales and one of the first retailers to offer credit to shoppers _ had become a follower in its decision to embrace everyday low pricing. The strategy, pioneered by discount chains, was recently adopted by <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, also based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and run by <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>'s younger brother, <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> `` One could say why not two, three, four years ago,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. `` Obviously, we think this is the time to make the change and we are doing it.'' Everday low pricing means carrying many national brands and offering them regularly at low prices, often with few salespeople. The shift marks a sharp turn in direction for <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, which built its business on store brands such as <LOCATION> Kenmore </LOCATION>, Craftsman and DieHard, with frequent, heavily advertised sales on selected models. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> acknowledged that the switch, which will be implemented this year, represent `` a major change for us.'' But he said it posed a different challenge than the `` Store of the Future'' changeover he engineered in the early 1980s. `` It's not as major a change as that because it does n't involve physical remodeling of stores and it will take place in a more concentrated period of time,'' he said. `` This is much less of a physical challenge than the Store of the Future. It's more of a marketing challenge.'' But, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said, `` it's important to note that you are never at the point where it's done. `` When we get to the point where everyday low pricing is implemented, we still will be changing and growing. That's one of the things that makes retailing so exciting: you're never there.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> is more than a retailer of merchandise. It's financial businesses _ <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Coldwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> _ brought in 42 percent of the company's $ 48.44 billion in revenues in 1987 <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> is comfortable with the financial-services businesses, but he grew passionate while discussing what he called `` the lure, the magic of retailing.'' `` There's a very specific challenge that you can see, feel touch and smell,'' he said. `` And when you address that challenge, you can see the results very quickly and you get a real feeling of satisfaction from that.'' On a larger scale, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> hopes to increase job satisfaction among employees of the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> by moving the 8,000-person division out of the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> and into more horizontal surroundings. The company has not yet decided whether to keep the division's headquarters in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area. `` When you are housed in a vertical structure, you have less people interaction than when you are in a low-rise, campus-type environment,'' he said. `` You have a more cohesive organization when there's more people interaction.'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, a golf and tennis player in his leisure time, called running <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> `` a very stimulating, challenging, engrossing experience'' but said he occasionally toys with teaching at a graduate business school. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Lois </PERSON>, the childhood sweetheart he married in 1955, have raised six children and some work for other retailers. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said he's never pushed them to join <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think it puts pressure on members of a family to work in a company where the father is in a high position,'' he said. Besides, `` it's not my decision. I think they're very happy doing what they're doing.''
