<HEAD>Dollar Surges Despite Intervention, Trade Report; Gold Steady</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar defied gravity in hectic European trading Wednesday, surging despite a bearish set of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures and two reported rounds of central bank intervention. Gold prices were mostly higher. Dealers were surprised by the dollar's ability to shrug off the bearish factors, and predicted the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency would rise further. News that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened sharply to $ 12.5 billion in November from a revised $ 10.3 billion in October surprised the market and knocked the dollar down, dealers said. The market expected a November deficit of about $ 11 billion. Dealers said the dollar's reaction reflected a markdown in rates rather than any heavy selling, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency immediately bounced higher. That triggered a round of concerted intervention by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, the West German <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> and the central banks of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, dealers said. Despite the first round of intervention, the dollar continued to climb higher, and a second round of dollar sales by the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> also failed to have much impact, dealers said. The intervention appeared to be fairly light, one dealer said. The dollar's recovery was aided by a few large buy orders that triggered a snowballing rally, a dealer said. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.7550 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.7680 late Tuesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Tuesday's prices, included: 1.8705 West German marks, up from 1.8505; 1.5890 Swiss