<TEXT>
 Following is a list of Japanese-associated auto plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The information is provided by company officials. _ <ORGANIZATION> Diamond-Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Normal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, a joint Chrysler-Mitsubishi venture, began producing <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lasers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> Eclipses in September. The workforce is about 1,500 and could reach 2,900 by this fall. By 1990, annual production will be 240,000 cars a year. _ <ORGANIZATION> Subaru-Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, next to <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, a joint venture of <ORGANIZATION> Fuji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limited </ORGANIZATION>, is expected to begin producing cars and trucks this September. The plant will initially employ 1,700 workers and, depending on the market, could expand to a workforce of 3,200 by 1992-93. By 1990, production of <ORGANIZATION> Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Troopers </ORGANIZATION> and Pups and the <ORGANIZATION> Subaru </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legacy </ORGANIZATION> will total 120,000 vehicles a year. _ <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> -RRB- Corp. in <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, began making the <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> MX-6 and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s sporty Probe in September 1987. It has nearly 3,500 employees and produces about 240,000 cars annually. _ <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Georgetown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, was dedicated in October. It has about 1,750 employees and produces about 360 Camry sedans a day. By the end of 1989, it will produce 200,000 cars annually and have 3,000 employees. An additional 500 workers will be added when a power train plant that produces engines, axles and steering components becomes operational in 1991. _ <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S.A. </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, opened in June 1983 and has 3,100 workers The plant produces about 220,000 Sentra cars and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> light trucks annually. _ <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, began making motorcycles in 1979. Auto production started in 1982. The company now has two plants at <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION> and one at <PERSON> Anna </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. It has expanded at <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> and is building a fourth plant in East Liberty, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The workforce is 6,700 and expected to increase to 8,500 by 1991. This year, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> is expected to produce 360,000 Accord and Civic cars, as well as motorcycles.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the only Japanese-affiliated plant located out the country's midsection, opened in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, in 1984. The joint <ORGANIZATION> Toyota-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> venture has 2,640 employees and produces about 200,000 cars a year. It manufactures the Corolla sedan and the Geo Prizm, a replacement for the Chevy Nova.
