<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market pushed ahead toward new post-crash highs today, shrugging off what analysts described as mildly disappointing news on international trade. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 13.75 to 2,228.39 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street. The average reached its highest close since October 1987 at 2,226.07 last Friday. Gainers outnumbered losers by about 9 to 5 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed issues, with 935 up, 513 down and 497 unchanged. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported this morning that the nation's trade deficit widened to $ 12.51 billion in November from a revised $ 10.26 billion the month before The latest number exceeded most advance estimates on Wall Street, although analysts said it caused no great dismay among traders. The news had only a short-lived impact on the markets. The dollar and bond prices quickly rebounded from it, and as they moved higher stocks followed their lead. Meanwhile, the market also absorbed the news of quarterly earnings from <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that fell slightly short of expectations. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, which posted profits of $ 3.97 a share for the fourth quarter against $ 3.47 in the like period a year earlier, was down -LRB- at 123 -RCB-. <ORGANIZATION> Tandem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computers </ORGANIZATION> jumped 1 -LCB- to 18 -LRB- and led the active list. The company reported earnings for its first fiscal quarter ended Dec. 31 of 32 cents a share, up from 24 cents in the like period a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> slipped -LRB- to 95 -LRB- in active trading. <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis <