<HEAD>Unisys Blurs Line Between Personal Computer, Mainframe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> introduced what it called `` the industry's first true desktop mainframe,'' a personal computer that has a special circuit board with all the features of its big mainframe computers. The Micro A further blurs the distinction between personal computers and mainframes, which were once as different as motorcycles and buses. It can can run either standard personal computer programs or programs written for its big A series of mainframes, <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> used advanced chip-packing techniques to get mainframe features onto a board small enough to fit into a single slot in one of its standard PW2 personal computers. The Micro A should help <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> against competitors such as <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which are also emphasizing their ability to run the same programs on big and small computers, analysts said. `` I think they've got something real here,'' said <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramowitz </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. But she said <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>' A series would still have trouble competing with the likes of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s new AS-400 line because there are fewer programs available for `` It's a positive but it's not a cure-all,'' she said.
