<SECOND>AM-Foreign Overtures, Bjt,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says 17 Percent of Biggest US Firms Wooed by Foreigners in
1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign firms made takeover overtures to 17 percent of the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies last year but only a handful of the approaches grew into a formal buyout bid, according to a survey released Wednesday. The survey by <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> also found that about two-thirds of the 95 chief executives who participated said they were more interested in joint ventures with foreign companies than they were in selling out. The findings were based on a survey of the chief executive officers of 95 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations with annual sales of at least $ 1 billion. Northwestern Professor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Zajac </PERSON>, project director for the survey, said he was surprised by the number of firms that reported overtures by foreign companies. `` Look at our sample _ those firms are very large,'' <PERSON> Zajac </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his office in <LOCATION> Evanston </LOCATION>. `` To say that 17 percent of Fortune 500 and <ORGANIZATION> Forbes </ORGANIZATION> 500 companies have been approached, that's a healthy number.'' But <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, managing director of <ORGANIZATION> Samuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montagu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the New York-based investment-banking unit of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, was unimpressed with the survey results. `` It surprises me that it's as low as it is,'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said, citing the takeovers by British firms last year of such notable <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies as <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It does n't surprise me at all that 17 of the 95 had been contacted,'' said <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, whose firm assisted in <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s buyout of <LOCATION> Macmillan </LOCATION>. Twenty-three percent of the survey respondents said they had been approached about a prospective buyout by a domestic company. The survey did not attempt to identify the nationalities of the foreign companies that made takeover overtures for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms. But a report released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Translink </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, an investment banking firm, said British companies went on a record $ 32.5 billion spending spree in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> last year, buying 398 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies. Japanese companies spent $ 12.7 billion on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> acquisitions in 1988, according to the quarterly British-American Deal Review, which is published by <PERSON> Translink </PERSON>. The Northwestern survey also found that while 60 percent of the respondents felt foreign ownership tends to maximize shareholder value, just over half said they would prefer a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firm as a new owner if they were taken over. Only 5.7 percent of the CEOs expressed a preference for foreign ownership. Sixty-four percent of the companies surveyed said they were involved with foreign allies in `` strategic alliances'' that ranged from joint ventures and licensing agreements to co-marketing agreements. `` I think that really shows how firms are adjusting to the new global economy,'' <PERSON> Zajac </PERSON> said.
