<SECOND>AM-Drexel, Bjt,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Wants Drexel's Junk Bond Operation Moved to New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the investment powerhouse that has agreed to plead guilty to fraud, is grappling with a potentially crippling government demand to transplant its lucrative and freewheeling high-yield `` junk bond'' operation from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Sources familiar with negotiations between <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and federal authorities, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed reports Wednesday that the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has added that condition as a basis for settling outstanding civil litigation against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. Making peace with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> is crucial for finalizing <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s record plea bargain deal reached last month with the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office on related criminal charges Under that arrangement, the firm agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay $ 650 million in fines and restitution, largely stemming from its dealings with <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the inside trader now serving a three-year prison term. A deadline for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to settle with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> passed a week ago, but the sources said both sides informally agreed to stop the clock in order to complete their negotiations. It was unclear why the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> added the new condition regarding <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s junk bond unit, a highly autonomous operation based in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> reportedly had asked earlier that only supervisory authority over the operation be transferred to <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters The junk bond unit is said to be the major source of profit for the nation's fifth-biggest securities firm. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> McCue </PERSON> declined to comment on the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> negotiations, in accordance with the commission's policy regarding impending enforcement matters. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> also declined to comment on the negotiations but suggested a relocation of the junk bond unit could be ruinous. <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> said the firm `` does not believe the high-yield bond department can be successfully moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> since any effort to do so would destroy the department and do irreparable damage to the high-yield market.'' Despite its lengthy legal ordeal stemming from the <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> scandal, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> remains a leader in selling and dealing junk bonds, which are low-grade, high-interest securities used mainly to finance takeovers and the growth of small and medium size companies. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> helped parlay junk bonds into a $ 175 billion market. The new <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> demand came at a time when many <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> high-yield bond traders already are upset over the firm's decision to bargain with the government rather than fight fraud accusations that stemmed from <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>'s disclosures when he was exposed in late 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> chief executive <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> visited the operation last week in attempt to ease tension there. But if <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> were forced to relocate the junk bond unit to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, many disaffected traders might quit, throwing the business into chaos. The operation was moved from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in 1978 by its architect <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> financier who is expected to be indicted on securities fraud and other charges. Unlike <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> has continued asserting his innocence but has been under intensifying pressure to negotiate a plea bargain.
