<HEAD>EPA Still Hopes To Move On Gas Vapor Pollution Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it still hoped to move further before the end of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration toward a regulation requiring larger gasoline vapor recovery canisters on cars. The agency's proposed regulation, and a companion rule requring refiners to lower the volatility of gasoline, has been held up by the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> since October on safety grounds. A trade publication, Inside <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, reported last week that <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, counsel to President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, had asked <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator, to take no action on the canister rule but to adopt the volatility rule. `` We are still hopeful that some type of agreement can be made that would allow us to take the next step procedurally,'' <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said Wednesday. Gasoline vapors are a principal source of urban smog, and the trend in recent years toward higher volatility gasoline has increased vapor emissions over <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> expectations. Several northeastern states recently adopted regulations of their own requiring refiners to lower volatility. Existing small canisters on cars are designed to recover vapors only while the car is running or parked, not the large amounts emitted during refueling. Recent <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> research has shown the higher-volatility fuel used today can overhelm the capacity of current canisters when running in hot weather. EPA estimates its canister and volatility rules together would reduce emissions of ozone-forming compounds by up to 30 percent in some areas. The Office of Management and Budget, the auto industry and Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a staunch guardian of the auto industry's interests, all have objected that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s plan would increase the fire risk in crashes A report from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said unresolved safety questions remain; <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s consultants have said the risk would be reduced When it published the draft canister rule for public comment, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged it would have to seek public comment again on the <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> report. In his comment Wednesday, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> was referring to that second solicitation of comment. That would not require the agency to go ahead with the volatility standard alone. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>' successor, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, has expressed no opinion on the issue. He could revoke any action <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> took, but such revocations are bureaucratically as complicated as the issuance of a new regulation. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> has been convinced for more than a year that the gasoline volatility rule, opposed by the oil industry, and the canister rule, favored by the oil industry, must be adopted together to keep the industry mollified if not satisfied. If the canister rule is not adopted, there is a risk that the entire issue of gasoline vapor emissions during refueling would be thrown back to where it was when it started 10 years ago, pitting the oil and auto industries against each other. The alternative to a canister rule is a requirement for vapor-recovering hoses at service stations, already used in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and coming into use in parts of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> area. The oil industry opposes these because it costs several thousand dollars to eequip each stations. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> believes the larger canister on the car is the better way to reduce vapors because monitoring compliance among two dozen or so manufacturers and importers on the device is easier than checking tens of thousands of gasoline stations using the dual-hose systems.
</TEXT>
