<HEAD>Camaros Take Top Four Spots on Most-Stolen List for 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Car thieves love Camaros. The autos made by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Chevrolet Division were the four most-stolen cars last year, according to a list compiled by an automobile valuation service in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. In fact, thieves picked <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> cars as their 22 most-popular targets, according to the list developed by <ORGANIZATION> CCC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a business used by insurance companies to determine the value of a stolen car. The 1986 Chevrolet Camaro topped the CCC list of stolen cars for the second consecutive year. This year's list, based on 1988 car thefts, has the'87 Camaro as No. 2; the'84 Camaro following that, and the'85 Camaro as No. 4. The top five was rounded out by the 1981 <ORGANIZATION> Oldsmobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cutlass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION>. `` It -LRB- the Camaro -RRB- appears as popular with thieves as with lawful owners,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Chevrolet Division. `` That car is extremely popular and if you think of a huge percentage of auto thefts being joy-ride kinds of things, the people who tend to go joy riding tend to do so in Camaros.'' The most popular imported car among thieves last year was the 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Excel </ORGANIZATION>, made in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. It was followed on the import list by the 1985 Mazda RX7 GT, and the'83,'81 and'82 Toyota Corolla, all made in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Of the 111,440 nationwide insurance claims handled by CCC, there were reports of 1,006 thefts of'86 Camaros, making up 0.9 percent of all the stolen cars. There were 780 thefts of'87 Camaros; 748 thefts of'84 Camaros and 673 thefts of'85 Camaros. The'87 Hyundai Excel wound up No. 23 on the overall list, following nearly two dozen <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> cars. Automobiles made by <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> accounted for 76 of the top 100, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had four cars on the list, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> had none and imported brands had 20. The first non-GM, U.S.-made car on the list is the 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Escort </ORGANIZATION>, holding down spot No. 45. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> cars make up about 50 percent of those on the road today, said company spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudgens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said the company has taken note of the high theft rate of some of its cars and is fighting it. `` I think the VATS system is going to make it a whole lot more difficult to steal a car,'' he said. VATS, for vehicle anti-theft system, was introduced on the Corvette and now is being used on Camaros and Firebirds, <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said. CCC provides an information database for insurance companies to settle theft and collision claims. CCC said the insurance companies with which it deals with represent 75 percent of all automobile property and casualty insurance in force.
</TEXT>
