<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Narrows in 1988, But Was Widening in Recent
Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> said Wednesday its surplus of exports over imports surged in December to a monthly record, despite official assurances that the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> economic giant is moving forcefully to open markets to foreign goods. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the surplus shrank for all of 1988, figures showed it was widening in the last four months of the year, capped by the $ 9.65 billion imbalance recorded last month. The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement coincided with news from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the trade deficit of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s most important trading partner, ballooned to $ 12.5 billion in November, the biggest imbalance in five months. Taken together, the figures suggested that simmering U.S.-Japanese disputes could worsen over restricted <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> access to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s markets, and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s exploitation of the American marketplace. For all of 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> reported, the surplus totaled $ 77.39 billion, down from $ 79.71 billion in 1987. But the figure was overshadowed by the December surplus, which compared with an $ 8.61 billion surplus a year earlier and $ 6.56 billion surplus in November. It was the fourth straight month that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surplus exceeded that of the corresponding month in 1987. `` We hear the voices of concern, and we have concern,'' <PERSON> Mitoji </PERSON> <PERSON> Yabunaka </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Second </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION>, said at a news conference. `` But at the same time, we see encouraging trends.'' <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s major trading partners have been pressing it for years to take greater steps toward reducing its huge trade surpluses by opening Japanese markets to greater competition from abroad. The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said exports totaled $ 264.87 billion in 1988, up 15.6 percent from the previous year, while imports climbed 25.4 percent to $ 187.47 billion. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s December exports grew 11.6 percent from a year earlier to $ 26.08 billion while imports grew 11.3 percent to $ 16.43 billion. With the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 1988 surplus totaled $ 47.61 billion, down from $ 52.10 billion in 1987. But the December surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> totaled $ 5.03 billion, up from $ 4.92 billion in the previous December. Lower prices for crude oil, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s most important import, coupled with strong demand overseas for Japanese-made computers, semiconductors and automobiles contributed to the record December figure. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> ran a $ 22.8 billion surplus with the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> in 1988, up from $ 20.02 billion in 1987. In December, the surplus totaled $ 2.15 billion, up from $ 1.92 billion a year earlier. For fiscal 1988, which ends March 31, <PERSON> Yabunaka </PERSON> stressed that the projected 23.4 percent increase in imports is better than initially expected and shows <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is `` on the right track.'' In fiscal 1989, the government sees imports growing by 17.4 percent compared with 9.4 percent for exports. <PERSON> Yabunaka </PERSON> attributed the 13.5 percent growth in fiscal 1988 exports to the strong world economic performance in general, and added: `` There will be a moderate growth in exports over the course of the next -LRB- fiscal -RRB- year, but we expect the speed to slow down due to a slowing in the world economy.''
</TEXT>
