<HEAD>IBM Earnings Rise 12.4 Percent In Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, The company's ..., to UPDATE with closing price;
picks up 9th graf, The pressure ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday its quarterly earnings rose 12.4 percent, a gain that appeared to reflect the improving health of the computer industry in general. Some analysts predicted that in 1989 <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> would approach and maybe surpass its record profits of 1984, the year before a computer industry slump that produced the first back-to-back earnings declines in <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> history. ``'87 and'88 were kind of recovery years. Maybe'89 is when we're going to break the all-time records,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> SoundView </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, who is bullish on <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> stock. Makers of big mainframe computers and engineering workstations are generally doing well while personal computer makers are muddling along, although results for individual companies vary widely. <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a personal computer maker, reported a narrow 3 percent gain in profit Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a minicomputer maker that has struggled in recent years, said its earnings tumbled 97 percent. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest computer company, said its profits were helped by increased efficiency and positive response by customers `` in every segment of our business.'' The <LOCATION> Armonk </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based company also announced it had trimmed its staff even more than expected through voluntary separation incentives. The company's stock rose $ 1.12 -LCB- to $ 125 a share in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. It had dropped as much as $ 1.75 a share right after the announcement but soon recovered. The pressure on <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s stock came mainly from the company's statements to analysts that its tax rate in 1989 would be higher than in 1988, depressing net income, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> and others said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 2.35 billion, or $ 3.97 a share, up from $ 2.09 billion, or $ 3.47 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $ 20 billion from $ 18.3 billion in the 1987 period. For all of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said its earnings rose 10.4 percent to $ 5.81 billion, or $ 9.80 a share, from $ 5.26 billion, or $ 8.72 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 8 percent to $ 59.7 billion from $ 55.3 billion. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said it recorded a fourth-quarter gain of $ 220 million on payments from <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, its Japanese rival, under an arbitration order that ended a software copyright dispute. But that gain was more than offset by a charge of $ 270 million to cover unexpected costs of consolidating its operations. The company said 6,500 employees had chosen to leave the company under a voluntary separation incentive program, more than the 3,000 to 4,000 that the company had expected when it announced the incentives in June as part of a $ 600 million consolidation program. The separation offer was made to some manufacturing and headquarters employees. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattia </PERSON> said it had been especially popular with heaquarters employees. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s results, `` It was a good quarter.'' `` Some hot money moved in to anticipate a better-than-expected quarter'' and moved out when the hopes failed to materialize, he said, explaining the stock drop. `` The <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> company is continuing to show improvement in our product line, our relationships with our customers and our financial performance,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said in a statement. <ORGANIZATION> Wang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Lowell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said its earnings fell to $ 1 million, or 1 cent per share, in its second fiscal quarter, from $ 34.1 million, or 21 cents a share, a year earlier. The office-automation company said revenue fell to $ 760.7 million from $ 784.7 million a year earlier. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said its earnings for the six months ended Dec. 31 were $ 14.1 million, or 9 cents a share, down from $ 56.6 million, or 34 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue edged up to $ 1.483 billion from $ 1.477 billion a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said its second-quarter earnings rose to $ 135.1 million, or $ 1.50 a share, from $ 130.8 million, or $ 1.46 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 8 percent to $ 1.4 billion from $ 1.3 billion. For the first six months of its fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> said its earnings rose 2.5 percent to $ 200 million, or $ 2.23 a share, from $ 195 million, or $ 2.17 a share. Revenue rose 9.2 percent to $ 2.34 billion from $ 2.14 billion.
