<HEAD>Livestock Futures Break Under Weight Of Supplies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Livestock futures prices plunged Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the combined weight of the corn market's recent collapse and large supplies of frozen pork bellies broke the cattle and hog markets Elsewhere on Wednesday, grain and soybean futures rebounded; oil futures surged; precious metals retreated; and stock-index futures advanced. On the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, live cattle settled .25 cent to 1.35 cents lower with the contract for delivery in February at 73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .90 cent to 1.35 cents lower with January at 84.47 cents a pound; live hogs were 1.32 cents lower to .10 cent higher with February at 43.60 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .45 cent to 1.78 cent lower with February at 40.55 cents a pound. `` I feel like the market's decided to stop selling the grains and sell livestock for a change,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hare </PERSON>, a livestock-market analyst with Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Linnco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. That was a facetious reference to steep declines in corn and soybean futures prices Monday and Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> following an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> crop report that showed larger-than-expected supplies of those commodities But another analyst said it was no exaggeration that the grain sell-off had spilled over into the livestock markets. `` I think it started on the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> after the grain report last week,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, senior livestock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` With corn down and beans down, it kind of created a negative overall psychology in the agriculture sector.'' Analysts said another factor may have been this week's sluggish pork demand, which contradicts normal seasonal trends. <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said the slowdown redirected traders' attention to the nation's growing supply of frozen pork bellies. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> reported after the close that supplies in out-of-town warehouses had increased by 736,000 pounds during the week that ended Saturday. `` January is supposed to be an out month for bellies, but we're not getting withdrawals on a net basis,'' <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said With no bullish news to support the cattle market, prices dropped below 3 - and 4-week lows, triggering a flood of sell orders from speculators who had been holding out higher prices Many experts have predicted that live cattle futures will rise to record highs above 80 cents a pound by spring. `` The well-publicized bull markets are often most vulnerable to a break, and there were tremendous bullish expectations for the cattle markets,'' <PERSON> Hare </PERSON> said. Corn and soybean futures rebounded on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in a largely technical correction from the losses of the previous two sessions, analysts said. And wheat futures rallied strongly late in the session on rumors that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was seeking to buy or had bought 750,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat for delivery this summer. `` I would n't be surprised if it turned out to be true,'' said <PERSON> Katharina </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat settled 3 cents to 6 higher with March at $ 4.39 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 2 -RCB- cents to 6 cents higher with March at $ 2.70 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 4 -LCB- cents to 6 cents higher with March at $ 2.37 -RCB- a bushel; and soybeans were unchanged to 8 -RCB- cents higher with March at $ 7.71 a bushel. Energy futures surged ahead on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> with crude oil prices breaking the psychologically important $ 19-a-barrel level and reaching new 14-month highs. Wholesale home heating oil and unleaded gasoline were up more than a penny a gallon. Analysts attributed the rally largely to a bullish trade report on oil production and to continued optimism that the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> will abide by its production-cutting pact that went into effect Jan. 1. `` It seems there's a general perception that the steps taken to shore up this market are no temporary affair ... and that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> has found the discipline it needs,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold and silver futures prices fell modestly on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange in reaction to the dollar's gains against major foreign currencies, analysts said Gold settled 70 cents to $ 1 lower with February at $ 403.30 a troy ounce; silver was 3.9 cents to 4 cents lower with March at $ 5.97 a troy ounce. Stock-index futures advanced strongly on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for March delivery of stocks represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 2.60 points higher at 288.70. The contract is worth $ 500 a point.
