<HEAD>Dollar Rallies Despite Worsening Trade Figures; Gold Slips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Money traders scrambled to buy dollars Wednesday and boosted the currency despite a surprisingly big monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, confounding conventional wisdom that when the imbalance grows the dollar drops. Moreover, the dollar's strength grew despite repeated intervention by central banks, which sold the currency about an hour after the trade report was released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` This is the last time we ever want to pay attention to the trade numbers again,'' said <PERSON> Zlatko </PERSON> <PERSON> Glamuzina </PERSON>, a senior foreign exchange dealer for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> branch of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> di </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sicilia </ORGANIZATION>. Gold prices eased in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion at $ 401.75 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EST, compared with $ 402.50 at the same time Tuesday. The big story was the dollar's resilience despite a surprisingly huge $ 12.5 billion excess of imports over exports for November reported by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Market predictions were for an $ 11 billion deficit. The dollar declined initially when the trade number was released, but quickly stabilized against key currencies _ a signal to professional speculators that the dollar was undervalued and they should buy it. `` It was a trade number that would indicate sell dollars, which was done,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Yannalfo </PERSON>, a senior foreign exchange dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> commodities futures firm. `` But then it stopped on a dime, buyers came in and the entire market realized the dollar was n't going down any further.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> entered the market at least three times to peddle dollars, but traders said the moves only slowed the dollar's rise and provided more opportunities for buying what they considered cheap dollars In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 0.20 Japanese yen to 127.90 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> it was quoted at 128.45 yen. By the time trading ended in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar fetched 128.64 yen, up from 127.83 yen late Tuesday. The dollar gained against the British pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where sterling fetched $ 1.7550 vs. $ 1.7680 late Tuesday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, sterling was quoted at $ 1.7535, down from $ 1.7707 late Tuesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with rates late Tuesday, included: 1.8721 West German marks, up from 1.8495; 1.5915 Swiss francs, up from 1.5746; 1.1906 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1982; 6.3825 French francs, up from 6.3065; and 1,370.375 Italian lire, up from 1,355.375. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with rates late Tuesday, included: 1.8705 marks, up from 1.8505; 1.5890 Swiss francs, up from 1.5755; 6.3800 French francs, up from 6.3085; 2.0925 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0855; 1,356.75 lire, up from 1,354.00; and 1.1937 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1973. In gold trading, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion for current delivery at $ 402.30 a troy ounce, down 40 cents from Tuesday. Earlier in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, gold remained unchanged at $ 402.25; in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, it rose 15 cents to $ 402.40; and in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> it rose 21 cents from Tuesday to $ 404.64. Silver bullion for current delivery fell 3.9 cents on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex to $ 5.905 a troy ounce In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, silver rose 2 cents to $ 5.94 an ounce.
