<HEAD>American Home Products Profit Up 11 Percent In 4th Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday reported its fourth quarter net income rose 11 percent from a year earlier, buoyed by higher sales in its health care products, food and household products businesses. The company posted a profit of $ 238.6 million, or $ 1.63 a share, in the three months ended Dec. 31, compared with a profit of $ 215.2 million, or $ 1.47 a share, in the same period a year earlier. Sales during the quarter rose to $ 1.3 billion from $ 1.2 billion a year earlier. Net sales rose by 7 percent for health care products and 8 percent for food and household products. Results also benefited from a lower effective tax rate due to changes in the federal tax code last year. For the full year, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> had a profit of $ 932.2 million, or $ 6.38 a share, on sales of $ 5.5 billion. That compared with a profit of $ 845.1 million, or $ 5.73 a share, on sales of $ 5 billion for all of 1987. American Home's products include over-the-counter medications such as Anacin and Dristan, household products such as Sani-Flush toilet cleaner and Black Flag insecticides, and foods such as Chef Boy-Ar-Dee and Jiffy popcorn.
