<FIRST>u f AM-Banks-Securities 1stLd-Writethru   01-18 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks-Securities, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0249,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Authorizes Five Banks to Underwrite Corporate Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs with congressional reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday authorized five of the nation's largest banks to underwrite corporate debt and said it would decide in a year whether to allow banks to underwrite stock. The unanimous decision by the seven-member board greatly expands the type of underwriting permitted, but still severely limits the quantity of underwriting. In 1987, the board approved bank underwriting of municipal revenue bonds, commercial paper, mortgage-backed securities and securities backed by consumer loans. In line with previous decisions, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said bank holding companies may only conduct securities underwriting through a separate subsidiary regulated by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. And, the subsidiary may earn no more than 5 percent of its revenue from underwriting activities authorized Wednesday and in 1987. The rest of the revenue must come from other types of business, such as the underwriting of general obligation bonds issued by municipalities and of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government securities, two areas that have always been open to banks. The five percent limit is designed to comply with the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act which separated commercial and investment banking as part of the reforms passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> following the 1929 stock market crash and subsequent wave of bank failures. In another restriction, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> prohibited loans from federally insured banks and savings institutions to their securities affiliates. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said it `` expects banking organizations contemplating major expansion proposals to maintain strong capital levels substantially above minimum levels.'' `` This is quite a conservative framework for conducting this activity,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradfield </PERSON>, general counsel of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. He noted that the board said previously it plans by mid-year to consider whether to raise the revenue limit to 10 percent. The five bank holding companies affected by Wednesday's decision are <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest; <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> The decision permits the underwriting of all types of corporate debt, including bonds that can be converted into stock, provided the convertible bonds sell for 15 percent more than the equivalent amount of stock. <PERSON> Bradfield </PERSON> said the board decided to see how well banks do with debt underwriting before considering whether to allow stock underwriting. `` The board felt it was appropriate to proceed cautiously,'' he said. <PERSON> Bradfield </PERSON> said once the banks show they have the necessary managerial knowledge, operational capacity and capital to safely underwrite corporate debt, final approval will be issued `` on a fairly automatic basis,'' perhaps as soon as 30 days. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s decision fits in with a trend in recent years in which advances in bank deregulation have come through administrative and court decisions. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is fragmented on the issue and failed last year to pass comprehensive legislation restructuring the financial system. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Oglivie </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group, praised Wednesday's move as `` another positive step by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> toward banking reform.'' `` This should increase competition in the financial services industry and lower cost for consumers and businesses,'' he said in a statement. However, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> action `` represents piecemeal dismantling of the appropriate separation which exists in the financial services industry _ a system which has worked exceedingly well for more than 50 years.'' The <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> has launched court challenges to previous deregulation moves by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, in his statement, said only that the <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> would review the decision. Two of the most vocal opponents in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of weakening the Glass-Steagall barriers criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> decision. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is on its way to giving banks an invitation to shoot craps with the taxpayer's money,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` This is the kind if irresponsible behavior that gave us the savings and loan crisis and brought about the 1929 crash.'' `` It's troubling that regulators would go ahead and legislate simply because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has n't done what they wanted it to. It's galling,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>
</TEXT>
