<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmacy </ORGANIZATION> voted Wednesday to define <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s new Premier `` smokeless'' tobacco product as a cigarette, beyond its power to regulate sales, despite critics' wishes to label it a drug-delivery device. The board also reiterated its request of two months ago that <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON> voluntarily withdraw Premier from <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> test markets, as well as its call for a rapid decision by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on whether the product is a cigarette, as <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON> says, or a drug-related system. The company again declined. `` We would not withdraw the product from the market based on a request from the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmacy </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Annese </PERSON>, a company spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>.
